\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
The next one to me was six years older than me. And the others were a difference of - two to three years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How about the brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
The eldest brother? Oh well he was - the eldest of the family. He was a good twen - a good fifteen - fifteen or sixteen years older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How about the other brother, was he in between the sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 The other brother was - seven years older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 And you all moved into the public house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, the girls were still in service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So it was just your mother and .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes, the girls were still in service, and when my brother was widowed, my dad's solicitor took my brother next to me, Ted - and - he was put in a - in a - a boys home at Farnigham. Put in by his - dad's solicitor. As my mother had too many to care for..

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When did your father die then, about 1904?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 My father died 190 - 1900. I was only about - I was on
ly about - not quite a year old when he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you wouldn't remember him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Don't remember me father, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You say he was a chimney sweep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes, a master man and he had his own gang of chimney sweeps. And - a carpet beating firm he worked with like to - contract the carpets. But all City offices, insurance companies mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did he come from around the City himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes, he came in - he was born in Mile End - Mile End - Mile End Mount, that's opposite the - that's opposite the - that's where the London hospital is at Mile End Mount. That's where the family originated from.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was your mother from round there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
My mother was round from the Whitechapel area. She was their only daughter of a - of a family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 She was a cook before she met your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Then - then she was a spinster and - 'course a - a cook general in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 In service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, in a local - local pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So she knew about cooking before you moved into the public house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh she was fully qualified that way, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was your father always a master chimney sweep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Always, yes, from a family - whole of the family - the - the Newberry's from the Mile End - had all practically the mainstay of the City contracts. Father had - four men working 
for him. See and - and one of 'em included his - one of 'em he - one of 'em included his brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Did your mother work after she got married, do you know how old your mother and father were when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I was the - I was the youngest. Mot
her must then have been about in her - round about her forties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was your father older than your mother or about the same age?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 About the same age, yes. Mother married when she was seventeen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did she work after she got married }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  you know, until your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, not 'til me father died. Then she went out - then she went out and was employed as a - office - office cleaning by one of the firms that father used to contract for. Housekeeper cleaner like to - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 She did that until you went into the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
She continued that - she continued that right up 'til when we moved to Stepney from Wapping. When - then she took over the household of the pub. Of the whole of the families.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Who would look after the children while your mother was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Mother was never out. Self employed on the premises like, lived on the premises, it was a big house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I mean before she started looking after the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Eldest sister, out of the girls. They had to look after -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You'd be quite a youngster wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Yes. I was a baby then, I was only - me first - be just me first year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You didn't have anyone in, any other women to look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, no, no, just the - no, just the - oh of course in those days every
body helped each other. But mostly - in those days - in - in that particular - district or our Court, Greeks Court, nearly every woman went to work in the City, either as - office generals or - in the kitchens. Anything - anything to earn a copper. Well m
y mother had no need to do that while my dad was alive, 'cos he was self employed. Self employed and had a good business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I suppose things changed when he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Changed immediately when he died because he was a heavy living man. And he died sudde
nly. It was a - just wasn't a - it was at the same time, chimney sweep, he was a hard drinker, and he went off like a - clipping a candle out. So she was left with six of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I should imagine they'd get a lot of fumes with the actual work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well
 that's why they were heavy drinkers. The dust. Yes. None of 'em - none of 'em had a - a - really a lengthy life. Unless they cleared out of it early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How old was your mother when she died, did she live on quite a long time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 My mother? Oh yes, she lived 'til she was seventy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you run the pub all that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh no. We - cleared out the pub when the war started, it - the first world war started, my brother - had to go in sixteen and - our - unfortunately - there was no - because every 
man had to - had to go and - it was 1915 that he - had to sell up. And what annoyed the family was that we had to sell to a foreigner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Not a German?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, one of the countries we were defending, a Russian Jew.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So what did your mother do while your brother was away at war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well my mother never relied upon me brother for a living, she always had her offices where she could always go back to. And the girls, one of the girls - one of the - all the girls by then had got married. They were mar
ried off. And we were a close knit family that we - not one let the other down. So there was never any need - need for - for want. Any time, the only time that we ever did want - was in the - when my mother - mother married a second time which she did whi
le she was in work, we lived in Wapping - was the dock - 1912 dock strike, and that - that properly - put the tin hat on all - all safety of the home, all little savings and whatever we had had to go in the pawn shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Who did she marry then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 A docker. Her second marriage. Married a docker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What did he do in the docks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
He was on the permanent staff of the Port of London Authority then in the old London and East India Dock Company. A crane - crane driver. She married him, 'course he was a
 widower and had two girls, who merged into our family, my mother brought them up - with the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So how many rooms would you have in the Wapping House?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh we had - Wapping house was rather a - a - a large house, it - it was rather a - a - all the old h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 ouses in Wapping were really - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 ig}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  housed because - they were built for the gentry of the old days, the - old wharfingers and - church wardens and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 etcetera}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 . Our little part of Wapping - was on an island between two bridges. You see. One - one pa
rt of Wapping, the real part of Wapping is - between two bridges. As soon as you got down - the bottom of Nightingale Lane - you crossed over Hermitage Bridge and when you got into - over Hermitage Bridge you was in that little island of Wapping, that sat
 
on its own. And to get out you had to go over another bridge at the end of the High Street, Wapping, to - make your way into - the other part of Wapping. And - our part of Wapping, in our little - sector - was the - more or less the Church of England crow
d
, and as you got over the bridge you run into the - St Patricks crowd. There's St Johns Wapping - and St Patricks, the Roman Catholic - church, they were wall to wall, they were right next door to each other, the only little thing that separated them was 
a little small ground, small playground between the two of 'em. They were both in - in the Wapping and - near enough by the - the graveyard, the grave - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} had their own graveyard, St Patricks - never had one. But the St Johns Wapping graveyard was right opposite the - church.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So how many rooms would you have in the house in Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well we'd have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have the sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes, we had at least four - we had a least four - four to - at least four bedrooms. And then a spacious kitchen and a big outyard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 A big yard at the back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Yes, a big yard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What kind of things did you have in the yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well we had nothing in the yard for - in the yard there because the - yard itself was more or less an old fashioned conse
rvatory, it had a - a - a glass roof right over it. Because it backed on to other houses, rather - old fashioned houses that backed on to - see - that lot of houses going up the hill from the entrance out of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Bermondsey Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to the Pierhead, that's 
where we were, right by the Pierhead, that was there, and our house backed onto that. See, so we had a big court - big backyard but it was a - all covered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You didn't have a garden or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, it seemed to be it was built - the - 
the house itself was - seemed to be a - a separate built specially for - one purpose - either a covered in courtyard with a glass roof or whatever it - it had a glass roof later but it was actually covered in. There was no yard, but we had a back - it was
 covered in by a glass roof.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would there be many facilities for playing out there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well there was facilities for playing out there, oh yes. But of course you - as I say you didn't need it because most of your playing was done in the streets. The
n because - after the - after the horse traffic had finished as it was mostly those days - the - and the wharfs had closed, the whole of the High Street Wapping belonged to you, there was broad acres. All cobbled streets and that was our playground, the s
treets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were there many neighbours children around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well the only thing we had to be scared of you see, we had - off of the High Street Wapping we had flights of steps leading down to the river. And - and that's where we all learnt to swim. But o
f course - a waterman in those days, the old rowboat watermen used to keep out eyes on us, for the simple reason in case the tide turned and took us away. Which in one instance I was carried away. I was carried away and - had the commonsense to - to - wit
h me small knowledge of swimming, I was then about - about eleven, and - I landed up - I landed up well down the river, when they picked me up. By a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 wharf side}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 , a boatman pulled me out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were there many people drowned in that river?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes, there 
was always a drowning. Drownings in the - in the - in - my young days as far as I can remember of what my - family used to talk about was that - somebody was unlucky. Especially the lighterman was working those days was very dangerous because the - the - 
t
empestuous winds that used to come up the Thames at times - would - would sweep 'em off the side of the barges which had very narrow - walking ways along the sides, on the gunwhales of the - barge, they were very narrow. Much - so much so that - in the wi
nter weather it had to be - you know - heavily - heavily sanded and gravelled, or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 whatever}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  they put on 'em, grit stuff they could do to - to - to counteract the frost and the ice. Sometimes - 'course they mostly in those days - they were old - old wooden ba
rges, they were wooden barges but - today now - well of course they're not used - they are used a - a bit now but - as time came after - they all - constructed in - steel, and the old days the - they were all - wooden, wooden barges.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was this house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hermitage Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Hermitage Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would it have a reception room as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh no, no, just an ordinary - as far as I - my memories as a kid can go - carry me -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Four bedrooms and the big kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes, you had a big kitchen, I can remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you eat in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh we all ate together, yes. All ate together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Who did the cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh well - well if mother was - if mother was out at work one of the girls.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What kind of things did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Whatever was going. 'Course we mainly - as things was a bit tight we mainly lived on - what mother brought home from her - cook generals job. From the restaurants where she cooked. So we always lived all on the pieces - the scraps that - which we could
n't afford, that she brought home. Which she brought home. And - of course we never starved. Our main - our main - our main - doings - butter was out of - out of the question yet it was cheap at the time but it was still out the question, we - were all - 
a
ll brought up on dripping, beef dripping or mutton dripping. But which I - which today I prefer now to butter. If I can get a good pot of beef dripping, as a matter of fact I've got - they do bring me one now and again, a friend of mine, when they have a 
decent joint. Beef joint. Still say it's the best substitute on the bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Your mother wasn't always out cooking though was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 She used to go out -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You say she used to do office cleaning as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well after the - after the old - afte
r - we moved to Wapping, then - then she took on the office cleaning. For a time she kept on the cook general, then she took on the office cleaning from one of the - dad's old contracts office, insurance companies, then became a sort of - major domo in - 
i
n - employing - get - giving her her own cleaners. For it, they used to have about three or four cleaners to a building. Well the insurance company had a - a couple of buildings, and she'd get the gang together, and - supply the cleaners. The cleaners had
 
- they used to get - had to be there at six in the morning. Or whatever suited the - housekeeper at the time, these times. And - they had to be off the premises before - half past eight. So that mean turning in there at least six in the morning, two hours
 
work. Then back in the afternoon, or the evening, when they finished, to do the heavy work. What they call the heavy work of the day, but the - morning job was polishing up and - setting the job - perfectly right for the gentry. 'Cos in those days it was 
- it was all - it'd had to be every - oh yes, had to be laid right on for the - there mustn't be a speck of dust about those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have many dealings with the gentry in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well - she - she - you - you get - you get connections b
ut it's all according what type you rolled into. Dad's solicitor was a firm friends, of course he - he - having - employing men and he had a solicitor - whose work he used to do, but whose contracts were drawn up by the - by the company he had, he used to
 
give 'em to his solicitor and he became - Mr Quick was his name, he used to be - he came a - a firm friend of the family when dad died, getting my brother away into the - the boys home. Take one responsibility off of my mother's shoulders. One boy. Becaus
e I was in - just a - a baby. And the girls and all went to service. All found jobs in service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So they'd come into contact, there'd be quite a lot of contact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
So they only came home once a week. To see mother. Wherever they worked, and they worked in very good houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever have any lodgers or relatives living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh we only had one lodger and funnily enough - a - a Mr James Mitchell, he was a Welshman, he come from a well connected Swansea family, and he - came down - as 
one of the - heads of the - tinplate people, the Welsh tinplate crowd - who started - landing the stuff at the London docks, and he used to be the - caretaker of their shed, and he married - eventually he come to lodge with us and he married - married my 
eldest sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was this when you were living in Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 We were living in Wapping, if we hadn't have went into Wapping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would he have had his own room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
He had his own room then. And then he - he went back to Swansea - went back to Swa
nsea for a time. And then - and then after the first world war, he - went out to his relations - in America, that's where my eldest sister went with her - went out to America and - that's where - she died, out there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would your sisters and brothers be
 still living at home when you were in Wapping or would they have gone into service already?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you were in Wapping, from 1904 to 1911?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
They were all there, the - they were all - when - when - when dad died - I was that, the boy was taken into doings and mother drafted the girls into service. To get 'em off }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 her hands, it was the only way }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So when you were at Wapping who was actually living in Wapping, in the house?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 In the house in Wapping was only - when my mother th
en had married a second time, she went to Wapping as a widow, when she married the docker - you see. And took his two children in - with the family, and there was only - only me, 'cos the others were in service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 And the brothers were living away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
And the boy - the other brother went - the eldest brother, he was a - he was away. He was in the public house business living on. Assistant manager, learning the trade. He eventually became a publican in his own right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house when you were in Wapping?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, no. No, no, no help. All the kids -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about when you lived at the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well that was the idea of - of us going to live at the pub when the - when the brother took the pub, the licence over, as a licenced - full blown publican, we moved in to supply the labour. Which my mother - soon adapted herself to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about the husband, did he do anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
And - he become - the step-father become - pot barman after his work in the docks. Li
ke collecting up the empty - the - doings. And I became bar cellarman, as a little boy. Then - seeing that the port was always filled up 'cos a lot of wine drinkers in those days. Port and - sherries and that. Cheap wine - cheap port was a - a great selle
r in those days. So you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What kind of people came to the pub? Was it mainly a sort of working area?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh well - oh well it was a - little bit - a little bit - in those days, there was a - always a class distinction. You were somebody if you used the saloon bar, generally the local tradesmen. Or the big wigs of the district.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Like who?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
And you had the private - then you had the private bar where it seemed to be - the - the nearest to those in the saloon used to use, then you had the publi
c bar, the snuff and sawdust bar, and then you had a little always a private off licence - a - a jug bar it was called, not today they call them off licence bar - but it was a jub bar, carry out bar, where you could go in with your jug and your - get your
 pint and a half of whatever, stout - ale, or - or Burton was the stout - stout - stout, ale and Burt was the doings see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What kind of licensing hours were there in those days, were they longer?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes. Oh yes, you opened at - you opened at ten i
n the morning. Ten in the morning - 'til - yes, ten in the morning 'til - midnight. Some districts eleven o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you'd be at it all day really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You were at it all day, oh yes, you was at it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you do this while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh of course when I went to school in Stepney and - we lived in the pub for a couple of years and then my brother married and - and - things didn't hit with the new - the new mistress coming into the home and that's when my mother moved out and f
ound a private house - quite - adjacent, not far away, a couple of turnings - well, just - a couple of turnings away from the pub. Still keeping friendly but - there's two women in the house didn't do see. Didn't operate. Mother always being like the lead
i
ng light, she couldn't see her way taking second - playing second fiddle. Owing to the fact that the - the wife - the new wife - was a daughter of an old friend of hers who - who - who mother had helped considerably in the hard times. So really - the - sh
e'd married well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You say you had these top wigs in, who would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 In where?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 In the pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh they're the local trademen, they were somebody in those -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 They were top wigs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes, they were - they were - oh the top wigs, 
oh yes. And the - well lay - laying right opposite the old Stepney church which was the - St Dunstan's church - was the Bishops church you see, he was - that was the head church. So you might get the - always got the bellringers in on practice night. Bell
r
ingers and they - they used to - they used to have the upstairs clubroom for their meeting. So they could dis - discuss their - their work, their different changes and peals they were going to ring - forthcoming does, which in those days that - you were -
 
you were - you could always - recognise - a church bells ringing, the different sounds and the different peals that they used to rattle off. But of course St Dunstan's church was noticed for a - was noted for its - set of ringers being a leading church li
k
e, the Bishop's church. 'Course the old - the old - the old part of that particular spot, St Dunstan's church - around that particular neighbourhood - which down the bottom of the High Street Stepney led into Stepney Green, the whole name of it, of the th
e old days was Steben Heath. Steben Heath.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What does that mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - it was - they - they - it became Stepney later but - that was the - the - I can remember be - being told that by an old Stepney gentleman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 It used to be called Stepney in your time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
It was called Stepney in my boyhood time but in the old days in the - in the very old days it was Steben Heath. Steben Heath. One name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What was the name of your pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 The Old Ship.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How many rooms would there be in that upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh it was a big old place, it's been rebuilt since it coll - it coll - it - it collapsed - with old age and they rebuilt it in - after the first world war. Rebuilt. It was a very old - very old inn. I can remember as a boy that breaking into 
- we got there, a man had had it for years before us. And we got into a loft, hadn't been used for - years and years and years, and we found old - cutlasses - old fashioned stuff, a lot of trinkets, me memory don't carry me back, I think there was one or 
t
wo - old fashioned - crystal things and that. And - I don't know what my brother did with 'em, whether he - handed them to the - I think he did hand 'em to somebody connected with the church who was interested in these - antiques over the old days. They w
ere more or less found that way and given that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So who would be living at the pub, your mother and yourself, your father?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well as I say, as I say, my mother - brother got married there, there was myself, and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Two sisters?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 N
o, no, no. Myself and - my - my brother. And me and me step-father. That's all, because the others were in service and only come home occasionally, and if they came home occasionally there was always plenty of room there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about the two daughters 
of your step-father, would they be out then as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh they were there, yes, the two daughters were, except one, the eldest one, she was put in service. The youngest one was her own -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was she your age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 She was - two years older than me. S
he was a - she was included in the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What happened to your other brother did he come back from this home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
He never - he - no, he only used to come on his summer visits, perhaps for a week's holiday - up into London. And he never came home 
'til he left the school when he was - fifteen. Fifteen and then - he was entered into the docks, on the staff of Port of London, the old - when it was Port of London Authority.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you were living at Wapping or in the pub was the washing done at home
 or was sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
When we were living at Wapping, no. There was no sending out in those days, you had to do your own scrubbing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Your mother didn't have anyone come in to help or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh no, no, no, everybody had to muck in. 
We had the old fashioned - old fashioned - row - my old - my mother - when we went to - live in - we moved from number {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}seventy Great Hermitage Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} up to a bigger house further up the street, number twenty-three. And my mother then bought - a - and my mo
ther bought a big - a big mangle but it was a big box I should say about - six foot long by about four foot - and used to go - you turned the handle either side, that was our job, and it used to go on four rollers, they used to press all the blankets and 
s
heets like an ordinary mangle would do today, but - was a much - much heavier jobs, and it's the weights and it was all - all heavy stones. Very - very old fashioned, very handy. No I haven't seen one - since. Well when she moved to number - twenty-three 
-
 and - she used to do - then go out every morning to the office work. And from the office work she used to take in a little bit of - of laundry, or work from the - I suppose the heads of the staff at the laundry - the special - shirts and cuffs, she was a
 
very good laundress at the same time and a very good needlewoman was my mother. So that she used to do the - heads of the firms she worked with or whatever it might be, the chief clerk or - or it might have been the housekeeper or whoever it might be, but
 
she used to get - a few pence that way, by a bit of laundry work. All in all - 'cos the dock wages of the step-father, was only twenty-one bob a week. They - they - he only got that because he was a crane driver - being a top man. Well of course twenty-on
e
 bob in those days was I suppose three or four quid - three or four quid today. Still - as I say - it only still run - it only still went to bread and dripping. Now one of my jobs was on Fridays, and the Saturday mornings - early, was to walk from Wapping
,
 with a couple of my - with my step-sister - up to Leadenhall market, get there before six in the morning, and line up to get - this - principally Saturday mornings. Fridays - we used to go twice a week. Fridays - we used to go up - on Fridays for the bre
a
d, that was the - stale bread that they knew that they weren't going to sell, bakers, so they used to let us have Wednesdays and Thursdays bread for a couple of coppers. Sometimes nothing, all according. All according to what mood the bloke was in - who g
a
ve it to you. And then from there on Saturday morning - we go to the meat market, Leadenhall market. My sister'd line up at the meat shops - on the ranks of the meat shops, used to wait on the kerb. Whatever meat shop was holding the line of kids. And I u
s
ed to do the poultry side. So that we'd get - a big bag of giblets for about - threepenny bit. And she'd get about five or six loaves for about a tanner, or a threepenny bit, whatever what - sometimes - sometimes for nothing, even a - if the bloke was in 
high spirits you'd have a - a couple of wets and he was a bit - bit fresh, bit boozy, you get it for nothing. And if he was hard up and he wanted to buy a - a drop more extra he used to collect, that's how it went.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So a lot of children used to do the same thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, yes, yes, more - over the water. They used to come from - all - not a lot from over the water but a few. But we were all - all known to each other, there was no scramble or fighting, everything was orderly, if one - one had got hi
s whack he used to go. But of course you - to work the oracle you always wanted two or three in a family, or a - or borrow a couple of kids from somebody else who'd come up with you, for the venture, if they wanted anything. Then you used to share out whe
n you got back home. So of course -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Where else would you get your food from then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well that was the only - as I say, once a week that was our kick up, good old giblet stew. And that was something in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you buy any food in the local shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh you could only - you could only afford a bit of a - you could only afford the old joint once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you eat that on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh that'd be Sunday's dinner, that was a slap up day. And the rest of the week - that join
t, you used to buy a big 'un - for a family, 'cos we was a good few of us at home, five or six, used to buy a - a - a good lump of beef. Always had a good lump of beef, and then - and then that would - that would become Monday's dinner. And Tuesdays - be 
b
ubble and squeak Tuesday and cold meat. Else it might go to Wednesday. There was no fridges in those days so you had to - well cover it with a butchers - butchers - with a butchers bit of muslin, whatever it was, and keep it - well down the cellar out the
 cool. The same time put a big - big box over it so the rats didn't get to it. 'Cos there was plenty of rats knocking about in Wapping at the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about your vegetables, where would you get your vegetables from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh your vegetables were rea
lly cheap, you had a little veg shop in the turning. Yes, they were reasonably cheap. And more so that - this little old veg shop - 'course they're - he used to go up to the - up to - up them - up Spitalfields - which was the market closest for us, and so
m
etimes he had a brother in the country, a bit of an old - a bit of a farmer way Romford way - when he got overstocked he used to bring up a load of stuff. And then we more or less - it was a give away. Very good of the old farmer. Bringing - the - relatio
n of the - of the people who used to keep the shop. Oh in those days it was all - all give and - all give and - all give and take you know; there was no harsh - no harshness, I mean if any - anybody was - you know how \{BLANK\}
 with new neighbours and friends and that, there was nobody if we had a bit - of a - allowed to go hungry. Not allowed to go hungry at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did neighbours come round very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, everybody about - everybody - everybody comes in. Oh yes, it was only a couple of coppers and a couple of coppers was a lot those days. OH yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you ever sort of have neighbours in for drinks and tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh have them round to - you might, yes, a cuppa, but they didn't - didn't run to the drink, the drinking business - the men - that
 was the mens - mens enjoyment - some women never touched it. But - if there was any drinking at all it'd only be on the Saturday nights. Saturday nights or - or perhaps - Sunday, but Saturday night - Friday or Saturday night - was a - the womens - if - i
f
 they did - and the majority of them never touched it. It was - you might have found the occasional - heavy one, the lonely woman on her - having a - her half of gin and - and that but - very seldom that you found the - working class women - with families
.
 Well the old men wouldn't allow it. I mean - they wouldn't allow them to use the pubs, unless - unless they took them. Oh no. They was a bit - a bit of an eyesore if it were - a woman was unaccompanied in - even in those little low down - boozers. And we
 
had plenty, in that little area, between the two bridges, we had at least - six or seven pubs. Yes. And - you could say that was under a quarter of a mile. Yes. As you got over the bridge you got the Scotch Arms, over the either side was - one on - there 
w
as always one see - you had one, two, three, it was about four or five steps down to the river, Wapping old stairs and - different - Wapping old stairs, new stairs. Generally named, if there was a big wharf near it, the - that had a name to it, but all th
e
 stairs have got their names off hand. I forget the - the - I know Wapping old stairs was my playground 'cos it had a bit of a - pull in for the boats. And I used to go down there with - with one of my lighterman's father's friends, Same Poke. Very old - 
v
ery old lighterage - very old lighterage - family. Father and son, you know, all down. 'Cos they have the - they have the - them and the Metcalfes had the rights of the road from - this side to that side, and the pick ups from the ships. 'Course even toda
y
 you can see the - the gentries houses on the head of - of St Johns vicarage, where the - the set of steps lead down, Wapping old stairs - set of steps leads down from one the big private houses, to the river. Where you used to come up - come up the steps
 but it were a walk right down to low tide, where the gentry used to land in their barges, you know, from there. Their - used to come up - 'cos a lot of river traffic was used in those days. Like - by the gentry.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you brought up to touch your cap and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh definitely. Oh definitely, you had to be very servile, oh yes. Oh yes. Everybody. You was a - you were - you - you had to be churchy. 'Cos St Johns, Wapping, I went to St Johns, Wapping school, which was a charity school too,
 used to get you - used to get your suit - suit and a couple of pairs of boots every year. But you had to war a cap, that was the - St Johns Wapping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did the school board run that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 That was done by - that was a - that was what you call a - 
a - a church - church school, that's supported by the funds of the old sea Captains who died, who were the majority of them all buried in St Johns Wapping churchyard which is there today. Yes, Wapping itself is desolate today now, everything - the wharves
 have gone. And the people - the whole - and the whole of Great Hermitage Street has gone. Almost float over it now. The school's gone. Globe Street's gone. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 It must have changed tremendously.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes, well the - as I say, it's the - as the c
hildren - grew older, the - practically the whole of the - only - the only - habitual place left was the - Hermitage buildings. The buildings people. Of course they were - then - if you lived in the buildings you wasn't so - so well off as those that live
d
 in private houses. That's how your - your grades of society you see would go in those days. Which - I mean - your boyhood memories you can just remember. If you lived in a house, private house in Wapping - you were somebody, if you lived in the buildings
 well you - wasn't so - you wasn't such a sampler.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was yours a private house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Private house, we always lived in a private house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you rent it or did you own it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Rent - rent it, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Who was the landlord, somebody local?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - well the dock companies owned most of that property round there. If my memory holds me good. I think the dock companies but - if it all - it was landed gentry. Landed gentry from - from the City, 'course the - Wedgewood Benn - was a - a great wor
ker for the district. He became the first Liberal - I think the first Liberal M.P. for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 The present Wedgewood Benn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
The - young Wedgewood Benn today. He came into it, I think he was about - he was about twenty-one or twenty-two - when he - he c
ame into it. Anyhow he was a young man, and we all voted for Wedgewood Been, 'cos his father had such a good name. Yes. I remember he was quite a young man, I was quite a - a boy at the time, all cheering for Wedgewood Benn, going round with a - this card
board stuff you know and a - a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did your father and mother take an interest in politics in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh - well they was all - the - the - the only politics they knew, they didn't know - as a matter of fact there was some couldn't pronounce pol
itics so you were all - all in the raw, my mother couldn't read or write. I taught my mother to read and write. Her - well all raw customers, not today, I mean, people today are - are super to what they were - in - in - our - my young days. - I mean - the
 
- the school I went to was - was a - it was - not because it was degrade - out of the ordinary, but you got more of the - you got more of the scriptures and you - you - than you did of the - of the learning, so much so that when I was - was - we moved to 
S
tepney and I went to the first - council school - from the church school at Wapping, they called me a dunce, and I was a - supposed to be a very top boy at St Johns. Instead of going to - instead of going into the high standard at this new school in Stepn
e
y, Trafalgar Square school, I was put in the fourth standard. And I worked like as though I was so - so upset with myself that I worked like a Trojan - everything I can lay me hands on in the way of books and every other thing, you know, I - I had it, but
 
they said I hadn't, but I knew I had it. And - yes, and so much so that - after the fourth standard I - I become top of every class I went into. Because I - I went into it, I must - I muscled in, you know, I was at the same time - always fond of me sport,
 but I wasn't going to be called a dunce twice. That was - always - that time, that teacher called me a dunce.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you see much difference between the two schools in the way of teaching?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh differently, you see - one - stuff that was put down to
 me was all fresh to me it was a - new world. The other you see, we were - we - was on - more on the religious side. You got - you got scriptures as soon as you got in, settled down in the morning, and very little of the - of what would be useful you to w
h
en you got to go our and meet life. See? Well when you went - when I moved to Stepney and went to this school - I was backward on everything. The only thing I was good at was - was - essay - and, well not essay, what do they call it - composition, yes, se
e
 I had - it was there, I had something. And - one of the teachers when I was in this fourth standard, Mr Walker, I remember him saying something to me, you'll have to do some homework young man, there's some good in you. And - I never forgot those words, 
I
 thought to myself, well - that's the first - that's first time any teachers ever said that to me. And we'd had women teachers at - in Wapping, so - except the headmaster, and he was a friend of the family, a friend of our family but - everything then and
 
there was taken in its stride I mean, as long as you behaved yourself you was all right, that was that, and - you knew that you - that - that when you went out to work you was either going into the docks or - or - messenger boy for one of the wharves on t
he riverside so - you knew - you knew your profession before you - long before you left school. The docks I went. The docks I stayed. And - as this man Mr Walker, he - he took me up and - when I left his class I never failed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you find them much stricter when you got to the council school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh def - well yes, definitely. Well you had - you had more - more - more - more work to do. Such - such as - what shall we - never - I never realized in me life - half a day - half a day a week carpentry, I m
ean you never had that - that - I mean, outside of - outside of home I never seen a hammer or chisel in a school. You got carpentry and - and - metal work you could go in for. At the school in Stepney, Trafalgar Square you see. So there you were. Oh it wa
s a new life to me, a new venture, it was something to tackle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What were the teachers like on things like punctuality or manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh, you had to be. You had to be at - you had to be, you ought to - you had to be at Stepney, you had to be on the d
ot. You were late if - you were late - if you were late that school gate was shut. 'Til ten minutes later, and you had to go in in front of the headmaster. But if you did - if he knew that you come from a big family - and - there was a difficulty in runni
ng errands and all that sort of thing, or - or do - or - any genuine illness, if there was any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 genuine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  illness - at all - was generally somebody - from the school would make enquiries, see if everything was O.K. As long as not to upset the boy or the girl w
ho - who's implicated in any way Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So that didn't apply to you did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. No, I was always good timekeeper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
You can't remember your mother or somebody being ill and your having to stay at home to look after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well my mothe
r was blessed with good health, yes blessed with good health all her life. The only thing she suffered from was what I suffer from today I think. It's - with - but with me it's hereditary because she suffered from the same thing as I've got, arthritis. So
 it must be in the - I had a bit of an accident and after arthritis set in, down on the left leg and I never shifted it. And my mother suffered the same. Funny. So it just shows it's in the blood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you were in the pub and still going to school did 
you say you did the cellar job, was that at the weekends or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - that was only 'cos there was - you got very little - very little bottle traffic in those days you know, it's all off the wood. No, my job was only just to - I was taught then, I
 was only about eleven, no my job was to keep the - and you - you - you didn't get bottles of port, bottles of sherry and all that, all - all come off the - the small quarter casks, you had down in the cellar. So my job was to - and then you had the cheap
 
wines - to keep the decanters full. See? Keep the decanters full or - or running the errand the customer wanted, like if we hadn't got - you - the customer wanted something or - and you had to go for the errand see. You was a - and collect up the - empty 
g
lasses. When there was no - police didn't - matter in those days because simple reason is that the - the old copper used to come round and have his - round the back - round the back of the pub there was a big - back entrance, so if you bring in a couple o
f
 ponies or whatever it was, it had a back entrance to it. And - that's where the beer - that's where the beer was left for the coppers, the gate was always unlocked, on different beats. They used to go on at - round about six o'clock. Well about nine o'cl
o
ck you'd - take out their pint. Or whatever - whoever it was, you get the ay-ay from him as he comes past on his beat you see. Four finger was the salute and some luck all right, that means to say, leave it there. If you didn't get the thumbs up - means -
 somebody was about. But of course, if the - Sergeant was all right - duty Sergeant was all right of that particular - week or night, whatever it might be, you - thumbs up. If it was a wrong 'un, no thumbs up. So you always got the sign.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you never have any trouble with the police in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No. No. Oh no. Never had any trouble with the police. You - if you had a - if you had a bad character you barred him, and then if you barred him, so your mates around, the other publicans put the shutters up as well. He was barred.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was there much drunkenness in the pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - they used to drink - a - a hell of a lot of beer, and no one knew they was drunk 'til they staggered out. See? That's the only time. And of course, men in those days - 
whether they say the - the gravity of beer is not as strong today as it was in the old days I'm no judge of that because - I can't say. But they could certainly drink their beer in the old days because - it was pints, pints. And of course as I say there w
a
s no flash bottle stuff, everything was off the wood. Now the pub, the old pull pump, there was no screw in the tap, now they get the bottles and all that, that'd come from the pump. And of course there way another job at nights. Last thing at night, was 
that - well if you didn't do it at night you had to do it first thing in the morning. Mind you, this particular house of ours, the old Ship, we opened up six in the morning. Six 'til eight. You know who that was for? Ay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 The early dockers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. Fo
r the - for the haddock smokers. Haddock - they used to go - and come there - come into the pub on the way to Billingsgate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What were they called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Haddock smokers. They used to - yes, they used to smoke - there was a couple of smoke holes in Wapping. \{BLANK\}
 Chuck sand down in the bars and round the front of underneath the surface of the floor of the bars - used to be - wooden rib right round about this wide - well not quite that - say that wide, and that all used to be filled with sawdust becaus
e - in those days spitting was allowed. And the overspill of beer used to come down there you see, and - the public bar - was floorboards and it was generally sanded. And it if - if it was well sanded it kept the floor - kept the floorboards bright, see. 
A
nd - as I say you - then the - in the fish business - the sawdust merchant would - would serve the pubs, and he'd serve the oak dust to the - his oak dust that'd be - oak sawdust to the - haddock smokers. So that they - all that he had to do, he go up to 
m
arket - up to Billingsgate, the fishmonger, as we had, we had a smoke hole down - by the way my mother - I forget to tell you, while she was at number twenty-three, Great Hermitage Street - had the offer of a fish shop. Opposite in the turning and - and -
 
she went into that, 'cos the lady - the family that had it were retiring - they wanted somebody to take it over so the - my mother took it over, the fish shop. That's how I come to know about the haddock smoker because - the man who did the frying - for t
h
e family, who left mother in charge of the business with the - with the man, the fryer, to run it themselves, used to be the splitter and smoker, so he used to smoke the whole haddocks down there and used to put 'em on long rods through these - split the 
h
addock and there was the two ears you know, you got a haddock, and they'd hang 'em up like that, and right at the centre of the room - there'd be this - this - sometimes - on a - on a big plate - and then - oak - oak dust. This oak dust would smoulder and
 
smoulder. The - contraction is that the - the - once the - the - the - hard - hard - ordinary round stones round, and this - was - sort of - once that got well started, smoulder, you pt the oak right over them, let it smoulder and smoulder. And it used to
 give a wonderful - a wonderful - dryness and the only - and a yellow colour to the - white haddock. Come out lovely, like - like - like butter coloured.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Going back to when you were living in Great Hermitage Street or Stepney, was - did your mother make the family clothes then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No. No, that's - no that's another job going, no, 'cos I - as I say - while I was in Wapping I got me clothes from school. And of course the others was out, there was nobody else at home, for two - the two children - from 
- from the - doing - from the second marriage my mother made, the eldest one as I say was in service, and the girl and of course I suppose mother made for her, I think that she - she - had most of - some of - mother was a very short woman, and the girl wa
s
 about - she was biggish built so whatever she did. My - my - my mother had a - always had a way of getting round things. Of course she used to get a lot of gear from the City. Well, give - given you know really. Oh yes, she had a lot of the gentry used t
o
 - think of the cleaners in the City. Where they used to - when things were - and no - in the big houses was no more use they thought nothing of bringing it along. Or not them, one of their flunkies, of bringing it along and give - and give it to the - th
e
 cleaners and - or - or - so - as - the servants in the big houses, if they had any of their own folk of course they used to come in for it. So it was always best to keep up big with the up - up and ups, see. That's why - yes sir, no sir - went a long way
 in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Were there many people in the area that would be called a real gentleman and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well we always looked at - yes, well you always looked up to - to anybody was a - that was a - especially the church. The church always
 looked up to. And your doctors. Doctors. They were the two number ones. Two number one frighteners then. Yes. Yes. If you was shirty, yes. And - and of course any leading - leading nob - nobility in a - in the - in the district, especially the - the - we
l
l - the head butcher, or the - or the baker, the head of the bakershop or that, they were all - top people in your eyes. See, they were somebody. Which today you take them ordinary sense, I mean you say - you just got a shop, that's that, so what. And in 
those days you - you looked up to 'em. 'Cos you never know what you wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You know that people divide society into different social classes or groups?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well in - in - in - in - in my - in my day - there only seemed to be - in my young days - up 
to the - up to the first world war, there only seemed to be two - two classes. That was - those who had it and those who haven't got it. That was the only two classes that you really that you know. Like - in the docks. Your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 warehouse keeper}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 , that was his r
ank then, that was the head guv'nor of your department, your docks was all split into departments and there was a - a warehouse keeper in charge of each one, and - in the London dock you had your vaults and the head one of that was a vaultkeeper, they wer
e all top dicks, and - they were somebody that you really - they were really controllers of your - your destiny. See? You - you had them all the - they were somebody in your mind. And what they said was law. They were guv'nors of you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What sort of people belonged to the same group as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - well you couldn't pick and choose in the working class. The only difference the - the - the - made the - the - the working class the only thing is was you was a bit - a bit better dressed than the ot
her bloke. Or you - had a little more than the - other fellow. In - in the working class. And of course if - if - you was in a family where so and so's old man was a foreman they were somebody. See, that's how it went. The position of the man. And -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 But there were different groups inside the working class really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
But - not socially. No, not socially. Only - in the sort of - the standard of outlook. You see? But socially you were - you were all one. There might be difference if you was in those da
ys if - a - a - where one the social side somebody - if we went to a music hall, our crowd, we could only afford - the gallery, up the top. Up the top for a - threepence, whatever it was. Yes, it was about threepence. Where - once a week or once a fortnig
ht those who had a few bob extra would do the - do the pit, see. I suppose that'd be about one and sixpence, see, that - well that was one of their ventures, that was - they were rated that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So income had something to do with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 In - money - ha'penny and a penny counted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Were there any families thought of as rough and others as respectable inside the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, you got your out - you - you got your tough boy. Oh you got your tough boy. And mind you - there was no use yo
u - yourself in - in those days of being - of being a weakling. You had - you - you had to keep up - you had to keep up with the - with the crowd. You had to be able to - to have a go, to - to defend yourself otherwise you was licked from the start. If yo
u was a pansy you'd have it. You know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you were at school were there any gangs of children in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No. No, no, no, no. No, you got your particular little crowd and - and - no, it was all help each other as far as my schooldays went then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You don't remember any one child say who was left out of things on his own?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
There was never, no, there was never - that - that - there was never - even - even the - even if - even if a boys was a dunce in the class, he - generally used to be good at sports so - well one - one - one made up for the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was there much distinction between craftsmen and labourers in those days?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, definitely. So much so - now you take it in Wapping, I can quite remember in my young day - if yo
u were a dock labourer or a wharf - a wharf hand, you were a wharf hand. But if you was a lighterman, you were somebody. See, they were freemen of the river, see. As a matter of the wharf wouldn't walk on the same - they were so - they had their own way o
f
 going on, they were that big they wouldn't walk - wouldn't walk at the same side of the street as you. Yes, we used to say in Wapping it was only practically in the High Street Wapping there was only one side of the street, the others were wharfingers. B
ut - the lighterman were the kingpins, they were the well to do people. See, 'cos they were master men.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Do you think your mother and father had the - saw themselves as belonging to any one particular group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 My father - oh yes, my father as I say 
was a master man in his own - in his own way and had his own men. Oh no, as far as my - what my mother told me he was a man's man all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about your step-father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh he was a dock labourer. Oh well, a permanent man within the docks, cr
ane driver. But he was somebody 'cos he was a crane driver. See? He was a - he was an all round crane driver.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What sort of people would you think went to church in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well you got all more or less, we - we - we went to church, I was in 
the choir - St Johns Wapping. I had to go to choir practice once a week and I had to go - to church - go to - to - Sunday school, and morning and evening service. So I - I was - I had my bellyful of - of religion, but when I - when I got to - Stepney - I 
f
ound I couldn't - the journey was too far for me to walk, from Wapping to Stepney all the time so I had to drop it, the choir and I never - never got - never entered Stepney church because I found that when I went to Stepney the church boys at the parish 
c
hurch there, St Dunstans, were quite lofty, they were somebody. They were the - well, they were members of the - local businessmen, sons of the local businessmen, and - you had to have an exceptionally good voice as a working class - as a - one of the - o
n
e of the down towners otherwise you weren't known. Unless the schoolteacher knew it, recommended you to the choirmaster or the - choirmaster at the school who - found out what church you attended and more or less you - you used to find out that if you did
n't attend a church school you - didn't attend, but my mother was of a severe - churchgoing woman and she insisted upon church. But not so much so when I got to Stepney because as I told her that -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did your mother and step-father go to church as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No. No, not me step-father. No, no, no, he was never - a churchgoer at all. He was a docker and - that was that. But me mother respected the church because her had her hands too full to - to ever be able to afford the time. I men the weekends was ca
tching up with what was missed during the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you have clean clothes to put on to go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh my mother was thoroughly clean, yes. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you have your Sunday best kind of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh you always had - 
always had to have to - always had to put on - and a - and a - and - do your boots Saturday night for Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Where would you get your boots from by the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well 'course we went - as I say, went - when - when we went to Stepney things had improved hadn't they. So I had - I - I was O.K.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you buy the shoes and boots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh well in those days, yes, as I say money - bought your - bought your boots and shoes, but of course then again, when you're - when you were a - a - a poor lad you ha
d to - you - you - always had to buy your shoes - boots - well boots they were, shoes then wasn't - quite known, you always had to buy 'em a - a size - a size a little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 larger}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  - so that you - as your feet were growing they'd fit you the - they'd fit you 'ti
l they fell off. Otherwise you bought 'em too tight - they'd fit somebody else. Oh yes. 'Course in Wapping we didn't wear - we didn't trouble about boots or shoes a lot, we used to run about in our bare feet because we'd be up and down the tide - the wate
r steps, to the Thames you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you'd get your shoes wet all the time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well you never troubled about them, you used to all - all - all more or less in - in bare feet. Only had to watch the - only had to watch the cobbles, see there was no gla
ss about. Well of course then - as I say - when I say glass, I say then glass about, there would be very little glass. You'd only see that because most of - you were only - the glassware only seemed to be - start coming into its own as I grew older, becau
se in the - in the - in the public houses it was either china pots or pewter pots.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to any one particular social group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh no, no, no, my mother after father - after me dad passed away according to
 what she used to tell me, 'cos I was quite an infant in arms, she found herself with the money run out for me. From me father, having to sell the rights of the father's contracts, me dad's contracts to - to - to the - people who were - who approached her
,
 and - her - her - well - well as I say, she'd never had a - she'd never had a - a particularly good - lux - lux - luxurious life - even when my father was alive 'cos as I say he was a heavy drinker. And - all he was doing was - all she had to do was brin
g the family up. That was her job. That seemed to be in that days that that was a woman's job. As soon as she - as soon as she was away from her spinsterhood - and she got married, there was children, children, children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was it possible to move from on
e class or group to another in those days do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well it's all according, I suppose it was a stroke of fortune, promotion in a family where a particular line. But when my mother moved from - when my mother moved from where - from the Minories or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Swan Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, Minories, where we lived, in Grigg's Court there - it was a case of necessity, because - my mother had - had started courting this - second husband, and he had a house in Wapping. So she moved into it. Didn't need - need to keep a house on 
her own while she could share a house with him and his two girls you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever have any dealings with the Guardians, the local Guardians?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, we never went anybody - to anybody for anything. Only - as I say - I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}St Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} school wh
ere you had your suits and - and boots supplied each year. Well you had one suit and a - and a pair of boots given each year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Did you see anything of the landlord when you were living in Wapping, would he come round very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh you had to pay
 on the nail every week. Yes, he called out - he used to call every week. Oh yes, you had to pay on the nail.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did he do repairs and things like that, what was he like as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh he'd have a go at his - no, you - no, you - you might get a
 room done now and again but most of it you had to do yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was he all right as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well you never used to see a landlord, you only see a collector. You wouldn't see a landlord, I mean, it was all - whether the - in Wapping, I think 
that - I'm not sure, I think that - the - the - the - ground there, all around our house - our area was owned by the old London India - London and East India Dock Company.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How about when you were in Stepney, who was the pub owned by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 The pub was owned then by the old City of London brewery. That's A.H. Tint.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have to pay rent on that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
You paid a - you paid a rent each year, you paid a rental on that. Paid a - but you were in control yourself. Pay the rent on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you 
were little, before you moved to Stepney, did you see many policemen around Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well you - you only had the one either end. We had one on the Nightingale Lane end, that was the - Hermitage bridge, and then used to have one at the - other end on 
the Wapping bridge who - do - Wapping and part of St Georges, while the other one he used to do from Hermitage bridge along the wharves up to the Tower. And of course when he got to the Tower the City Police took over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Do you remember being told that if you're naughty I'll send for a policeman?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, we - we used to have - we used to have - we used to have a - a - a policeman who used to stop us playing football round the back wall. Well I don't know 'cos we wasn't hurting anything 'cos there -
 there was the dock wall there and there was only one or two - couple of houses or whatever it might be and then a factory. But he was insisted upon us stop - stopping us playing football round there. And football used to be - I might tell you wasn't the 
f
ootball that you see today, the football was a - a sack - made up of sawdust and rags, see. Perhaps a - might have a - an - inner leather doings or - or whatever we could make round, and - I remember - that we was given a - somebody - whether it was some 
d
ockers - gave us a football, and - oh we was tops then. And when old Bloodknutt come on he started his beat, he pinched our ball. He pinched our ball and as far as we remember he - he - he knifed it, pierced it. So what we did in vengeance was - they used
 
to - used to - coppers then in those days used to - always have to go on duty in the winter with their very heavy tarpaulin cape. So we pinched his tarpaulin cape, where they - we know they used to leave - used to leave it, they used to put it over a litt
le gateway round back of - round by the Scotch Arms. The name of the pub. And we chucked it over {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Hermitage{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes. He never found - never found out to this day. He - he done our football, we done his cape. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Do you think he treated the people well in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes, policemen on the average, we generally got the - the firm - you generally got a firm one. One sometimes who liked kids. Sometimes who was a - well you had to be a bit harsh - I think - they had to be a bit - a little bit stif
f with us kids in those days because - I mean - we took a chance on everything. Yes, we took a chance on everything. Well as a matter of fact - old Morocco wharf, down on the ; on the - over the - over the Hermitage bridge - over the Wapping bridge, down 
o
n the right hand side, Morocco wharf, used to be in the season - used to come with orange ships, fruit ships. And we'd - of course it was all horsedrawn wagons in those days you know. And we'd wait for the - vans to go along, and - sometimes they might ha
v
e a look out on - sitting on top of the - for to see to the doings. We'd always break a case of oranges open at the back, pinch a few oranges and dive down the side turning. But - but - you - you couldn't get caught 'cos you had - well you couldn't get ca
u
ght 'cos you had one - couple of the boys policing the copper, occupying his time wherever he might be, while the rest of the gang was doing the raid. But of course it was only - they was only petty, when you come to think of it. If you'd - if we'd have -
 if we'd have gone down the wharf - our own relatives would have filled our hats and our pockets with loose oranges. Yes. Part of the excitement was getting an orange out of the case.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you mainly play round by the wharves and the docks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh t
hat's all our life was. Oh - that's all we - the only pleasure we had was that. And down by the river. I've learnt to swim off of Wapping Old Stairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What other kinds of games would you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh - football and cricket. It's only thing we knew. T
hey was the main games. You might do - well cop - well coppers and robbers I mean this - was - that - that never came into it, it was always - football or cricket. They was just your selection.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever play inside the other childrens houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh - well of course you would do, but that - that only be if - if the - that'll only be weekends when the parents was out. Parents was out, can my - my crowd come and - you know - the - whoever they friendly. I don't want to leave my kids on their own, c
ome in with yours and there'd be somebody there, be a - one enough - old enough to look after 'em. And if we got stowed we were all right then because - generally - generally to keep us quiet - ginger beer was very cheap in those days. So they - we'd get 
-
 we'd get a couple of jugs of ginger beer - brought round, or a - or a - something - that the house had made. Some - lemon or something. Lemon squash, what - whatever they'd made. Or if not you got a - what - was a staple then, which was cheaper was the -
 hot cup of cocoa. That was the - cheap one.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you play games and things like that in the houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well it's all according what you have wasn't it. I mean you never had the - you - the - you - the - the - all that you had was ludo and snakes 
and ladders. But you knew of, as - as - so - oh cards. Of course you got the - those who could play cards, then you - they started the gambling, but - you soon know how to play cards soon after you left school, you soon picked that up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What did your mother think of playing games on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh very strict against that. Oh no, no, no, no, you never - oh no. I can even remember - when - after the - after the - the - first world war, when - I used to be rather a - a good soccer player, I started - tu
rning out Sunday mornings for pub teams, 'cos a - a lot of - pubs in the East End - and around - Wapping and - Cable Street and - all around the Stepney area had - Sunday morning teams. And - if you joined up with one of them of course you become - illega
l to play on a Saturday afternoon. You became a - a nonner, but - as the years got on I used to play - both, I used to have a game on Saturday and a game Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever do any school sports or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, only - only - I - I rep
resented the school in - high diving. High diving in - in the swimming. I used to go in the relay team if they had a relay team in swimming. Hundred yards. But - there was any speciality - it was only - diving competitions, high diving in the school, I us
ed to get - entered for that, picked for that. Which I used to be very good at because - I'd learnt to do that side of the - in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Thames{\*\xmlclose} you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How old would you be when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh - oh I must have been about - five or six - or four, be very young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did your mother take you to school or did you make your own way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, only went to St Johns Wapping, you had a - there was - toddle off to school on your own. Oh yes, well it was quite near you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have school dinners or anything in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh no. No, never got no school dinners, you might - you might get a bit of a - a treat, now and again. Specially round about - Easter time, you'd - Thursday before Easter you'd be give - get some hot cross buns 
given to you - might get a cup of tea, but not otherwise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So what did you do, you came home from school for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes, you was home from school. All your meals at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Who would be there to cook the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well if they was out at work you had to wait 'til night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you didn't eat a midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
They'd leave something. Could be - bread and cheese or - sandwich or - whatever was left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What would you have for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Of course you could always get plenty of m
ilk in those days, so you'd have a - a - a mug of milk. Oh breakfast, we always got Quaker Oats. Quakers Oats and bread and dripping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would everybody be there for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well of course all those that was working, those who were working got a
 - might get a fried egg and - fried egg and a - and some - and some - bubble and squeak. Bubble and squeak is the - veg left from the previous day fried up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What time would you have the evening meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well, it's all according. If you had your di
nner out - you had an ordinary tea when you come home but - those who - used to make do with sandwiches for dinner, who - when they went to work - had evening meal when they come home, whatever was going or whatever was - they could get. But of course it 
w
as all right in the docks. When I started work in the docks as a messenger boy - we had our own - each department had its own dining rooms, or one - or - perhaps two department's would use one central dining room. And - that was the time - that was the fi
rst time I - I start seeing real - real grub. Yes, we weren't badly fed at home, my mother saw - saw that we had plenty of everything. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about when you were in the pub, wouldn't you have good food then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well you see, I was young then wa
sn't I. I mean I - I - I hadn't got the full weight of - of - of the grub situation. I mean, I hadn't got out of that stage of where - a couple of slices of strawberry jam or a couple of slices of - of bread and dripping and - whatever it might be was goo
d
. I was still used to that one slap up Sunday every week. But when I got into the docks, start working as a boy just before I was fourteen years old, they had their own kitchens - and being a messenger boy you automatically became - waiter at dinner - lun
c
htime, taking the dinners from the serving hatch to - the staff sitting around. Well for that - you used to take it in turns. There was three messenger boys on a department, or two. The two of you could work together and get a - have a - have - then you u
s
ed to get a slap up dinner, so - I come into me own when I started as a messenger boy, I had a - a smashing hot dinner every day, of - and it used to be - the cook used to see it was the best. Because it was - you had it after a - all the others had finis
hed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You say your mother was a cook as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well she bought - she bought - now - well she - the way she fed us when she was widowed, she used to - be able to - take all the pickings of the day from the restaurant or wherever she was working, bring it home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would she ever make things herself like bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh - not bread, no. She - no, she was very good pastry cook. Very good - very good pie. But never bread, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did she ever make her own jam or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No - never we
nt in for the - no, never went in for that, we - she used to buy - buy - a stone jar of jam, and mix - what you call - mixed jam, or - generally used to be a - a stone jar of mixed jam. And that used to be always kept covered so if you wanted jam you alwa
ys had a stone jar full of it. None of the fancy bottles what you get today and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 She wouldn't make anything like her own pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh no, no time for that boy, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What kind of stove did you have in the house in Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Closed in range you know. One of those closed in - black things. Fire there and a big oven on the - left hand side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 And you say you always ate in the kitchen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Always ate in the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about when you were in the pub, did you have a special room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well of course you'd have - the pub, now the - in the pub there we had - a - a kitchen we had a kitchen and the dining room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you'd eat in the dining room there would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well - we - we - dining room, you know, you'd lay 
out on the Sundays, but then - as I say, in a pub - you - you never had that time for splendour because you was open so many hours. Everybody was doing their turn. You couldn't expect a man to open a pub in the morning, as they used to open here - ten or 
e
leven o'clock, and carry on 'til midnight and be there all the time. So it was either - changing. So what the man did in the morning, my brother - used to open up the pub, get it a going, then any business he had to do - he'd go and do. See? Outside. Ther
e
 was no like - you post your order and all, they - you had to take it. Were no phone business. See it was all foot slogging, I'm going back now to before the first world war, you see. There was - was post but it was quicker - it was quicker for you to foo
t slog it, see, you didn't have far to go. And then - that was - who was the - oh City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 brewery, well a quite - their offices was - quite handy. And of course then - City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London Brewery{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 to - who bought them out now - Charringtons. And Charringtons bought them out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
You say you used to drink milk quite a lot, what other kinds of drinks would you have with meals in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well you only got plain milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You wouldn't have tea or coffee?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, no. No - cocoa was your main. Used 
to get tea you know but - cocoa seemed to be the - the mainstay. Mainstay. Coffee was the - you - very seldom heard - coffee.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Before you got into the pub would you ever brew your own beer or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You wouldn't have any garden to grow vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Nothing at all, no. Just a back - just a back yard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Or any livestock?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
When we went private in Stepney, yes. My mother had - my mother then went in for - for poultry. One side of the yard we built a - w
asn't a very big yard. Wasn't a very big yard, I should say it was about - her - from here, where my knee to the door. And about - you know, about that wide. You know, about the width of this. Very small yard, but one side of it had a bit of a - a - waste
g
round like about - I should say about - width of that carpet, so we built a chicken run - on that. And - used to do well at the egg lark. That's it, used to do - that's where we used to do well at the egg lark and there was always a - always - and - my mo
ther - and - my step-father, then me, we become - slightly expert in the chicken game that we always had a - a full lot going on you know, well - always had a chicken handy for a - for the pot or for the - or for the roast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you have things like tinned food or tinned fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Very little. Very little, the only thing that we used to - to really - really get was bully. Corned beef. Corned beef used to be - about - used to be a - a - a day when - when the new potatoes was in, corned beef used to b
e a good feed. And we - of course we used to buy it then in the - the - in the big tins. So that she bought a big tin there was too much for you, you can - halve it with a neighbour, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 At mealtimes do you ever remember seeing your mother eating les
s food so that the rest of the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, no, we always had - no. My mother always - sat down last. And - if she sat - we used to - as we got older we insisted upon - us doing the carving and her sitting down. The girls do the cookin
g. But when we was quite - young, she'd always have her own - and she's all - always a good eater.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 She did the serving and everything did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 And she - any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
How would she serve the meal, would she serve it from the stove or the table or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - in - when we was - private - when we were private in the - in - after we - left the pub. Oh she'd serve up the dinners. Yes. She'd serve up the dinners. What she used to do, if she had a joint she used to cut the meat - she'd have a - ordi
nary dish you know, enamel dish, and she cut all the meat up, that would be in hot gravy, she got all the - cut that from a joint, she cut sufficient meat - for the crowd and would be soaked - be soaking in - stock - stock, like gravy what they call - she
 
used to call her stockpot, in that gravy. That would be in the oven, or in the stove, whichever - what - what we had then. We had a kitchen stove there, I forget where - she put it. But all the cut meat would be in there. Then when the veg was ready, the 
c
old joint - the joint then would go into the - the - larder, out in the yard, not inside. Built a - in the yard in Stepney we built a - a box, put a - a wire mesh in front of it and - you know, just minute - mesh, and - so the air could get through, so al
l
 our fresh stuff went out in the yard. Behind that mesh used to be a bit of meat muslin, so that no dirt could pass through see. So when the joint was finished with it used to go out in the yard in the - safe, be off the ground about as high as that telev
ision. On the wall on two brackets. So the - we - that - nobody could get at it, not even the cats or - anything. So it was always out in the air.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Can you remember your father having more food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Step-father, no, I never knew me father. Me step-fa
ther, no. He'd only - he'd only go out in the - in the morning - with his pocket of sandwiches. He was always working - late in the docks. So - you know, they have a - a snack when he come home. Or - or if he was going to be early there'd be - whatever we
 had for dinner, he had - we kept for him at - on the boiler, heat it up on top of the saucepan when he come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
My mother didn't like it, but - it was very seldom we did. We always got on with our food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
And if there was something else you wanted like the salt or something could you just help yourself or would you have to ask for it or wait for it to be passed to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well generally - generally - then - you - you just - you used - you used - then we - you might put a bit of salt on, a bit of pepper but my mother used to flavour her food while cooking, so you really didn't need any. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh no, no, no choice. No, no. What was on was on. If you didn't like it, well you were unlucky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What was the situation if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh no, it was always sufficient - or you could go and - you could go and have another go. Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork and sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes. Yes, you had to do that. If there was any scooping up or even with a knife in our house - you soon got a bash.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Could you bring toys or books to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you'd finished. When you finished, you was in a hurry, going now mum.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You didn't have to wait until everyone else had finished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh no. Going now, mum. I'm off. Right-o, don't be late.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
And you say sometimes your step-father wouldn't be there, so it wasn't sort of all the family round the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, it was never - no. No. He used to come in - they were all broken hours. So that - you - you knew where your dinner was, you were told that in the morning, where it'd be, so you knew where to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have the same places at the table when you all sat together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
More or less you kept your own place, yes. When we sat together, yes, always had our own places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was there any special order you were served in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. No. Only - it only took - took mother one spot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How did you get on before you were old enough to feed yourself, who fed you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 My mother was - well - my eldest sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you be at the table itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh I shouldn't say where I - how I got on. I couldn't say that. The - the - I know that me - sisters brought me up while mother went out to work. After she was widowed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Do you remember if your step-father helped your mot
her with any of the jobs in the house? Like decorating or doing the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, he was no good, he was just a docker. No good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 He didn't help with the washing up or the cooking or anything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, not at all. No. That's what my - my - my moth
er wouldn't have - wouldn't stand for either. She said that was a - the work - the women - the girls jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did he ever help to dress or undress you or give you baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did he ever read to you or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Do that - no, he w
as too ignorant for that, I was more - I was more - I could tell him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did he ever look after you when your mother was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. No. Had to look after ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Did you have any tasks you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and step-father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes, my job was - windows and knives and forks. Every week. Windows to do and - knives and forks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You did that every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Every week that'd be done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When did you give up doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 As soon as I went to work.
 Well I did it for some time afterwards still - 'til the - somebody'd - take a turn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
You say your eldest sister used to help you when you were very small, did you do anything for them, I suppose they'd all be left home by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 They'd all left }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 home by}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  the time I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Did you ever do anything for the other sisters, the daughters of your step-father? Anything to help them in any way or did they help you in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well of course, the - the girls were against the - the step-father. They
 - couldn't understand mother ever - marrying him, but I think it was a case of necessity why she married, for the simple reason that - that - he had two kids, he had two girls, and she had us - herself, and - and me brother, I suppose it was a - a good -
 he wanted somebody to look after his girls and - mother wanted a few more bob - sort of financial agreement I should imagine. Well anyhow she never sort of gained much by it 'cos she lost one heavy drinker and gained another one. A beer drinker.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What time was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 She always liked us in bed round about nine. Before nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh looked after yourself. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Your mother didn't put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. No. Oh no, you got no pansy - stuff there, you - do for yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have your own bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh no, shared. I shared the - I used to - there was - how many, there's three of us at home then. Yes, we used to - share.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about the two sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well I say, the eldest of the two sisters, she went to service, and - I was in with the other one, the other girl who was at home. Her father -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Your mother and step-father had the other room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Yes.
 Yes. And the - in Grosvenor Street they had their - downstairs room, and - and it was a double front, the entrance was in the centre, room right and left. That was a sitting room, we - well called the parlour, and - our bedroom was upstairs. And attached
 
to our kitchen like - there was a kitchen, there was a door led to another little small compartment, and which was only used so we - but as time went on we got a bath put in there, and - got a friend to do the plumbing, and - and a table top made to put o
n top of the bath, which served as a service table for the back kitchen, the cooking and all that so - all the carving was done on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was this in Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 In Stepney. No, no bathroom. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How often would you have a bath?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh regular Fridays. Friday nights.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 And would you have clean clothes to put on on Friday nights?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Always. Always a change. All had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh definitely, oh yes. OH yes, she was the - she was the - the handy -
 the handy - one for advice in the turning, and the first to call - the first one to be called upon to produce a new born baby, that's when - when - medical aid wasn't so prompt or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 She was a midwife was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well - selfmade midwife, yes. She was - used to do all the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did she show much affection to you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Very fond of - very fond of children, mother. Well she should be, she had as I say - nine of her own so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 And did you find her affectionate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh she was all family.
 All family, all for her kids, she'd go out and fight in the street to defend her children. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So if you had any worries you could take them to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh she - I - I've seen in Wapping in the old days when - when - there was any - any battles at all, and - any of our - any of our crowd were - were - implicated in any way, she'd be in the battle. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did that happen very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Not often, it's generally on the weekends that - you used to - when it stirred up, when the - when the 
- the beer sessions created at home in the old days as you know that they used to make the weekend their beer weekend. They didn't run to it during the week 'cos the wages wouldn't allow it would it. But at the weekend - Friday and Saturday night used to 
b
e a - the sing-song night. No, you didn't find much pub crawling in the old days, most of the old - old inhabitants, the men - or the families, always stuck to their old - their own local, you know, that - well so much so in several of - my people - who -
 who were a - became interested in the licensed trade of latter years, but in the early years I can quite remember that - regular customers used to have their own - pewter pot hanging up. Duly attended to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did he ever drink in the home, your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, my mother never drank. Never drank, no. They had very little, only in a - in a - celebration occasion. Or Christmastime or a birthdaytime or - there was a little bit of a - family gathering.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How about your step-father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh ste
p-father was a drunk. Oh yes, he was a - he - he'd leave off work in the docks at five o'clock and he'd tail himself in the pub 'til eight. And - then come home. And - my - might have a - well, wouldn't have a meal, just - just a - perhaps clean himself u
p or perhaps not, and - into bed, but up in his own room, because after a number of years, when we moved to Stepney, he - my mother made him take a separate room owing to his habits getting a little bit - I suppose - out of hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How did you find your step-father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well, as a matter of fact, I was the master of my step-father for the simple reason that - that - owing to his bad - as I say, his drinking habits and I was a - more of a - very church - well I wasn't a - a stiff religious but I was atta
ched to our church, sports activities and all that sort of thing and - and - I - I realized he could - he could do better and I took him over - for a time, as I - after the first world war when I come home I took him over and - and - being in the docks an
d
 on the same department near enough, or not far away from him - I used to make him - if I wasn't working late, I used to - make him wait for me at - five o'clock when he knocked off home and - just allow him - to have a pint at his favourite pub near home
 and then I used to say to him, I'll give you - half an hour. I want you home. Because I became master of him because I'd grown up and was - back from like from the first world war and I told him he didn't have to - he'd have to mend his ways.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How did you get on with him when you were in Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh well, that's what I say, that's when - that's when the dreadful mistake that my mother ever made was every marrying a second time. That was actually the cause of the - family breaking up, and - the gir
ls going into service, which my mother always wanted them to do which they wanted to do. And my eldest brother being in the licensed trade, which he was apprenticed to when he was about - quite young. Well it wasn't a case of apprenticeship, he - he liked
 
pubs and he went into the pubs quite a - leaving school age. And - continued in that - in that profession through his career 'til the - first world war, when he - had to go in the - in - into the forces. As I've said before, he had to - through our - thro
u
gh our own way of reckoning was a great injustice that we had to sell to - as I say, to a Jew, a Russian Jew to - who was the only part - person available - to take over the licence, as most of the - local lads and men had - been called up or volunteered.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did he go back into it afterwards though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh he went back into the trade after he left the - the forces. Yes, he went back into the trade and took a pub over at Rotherhithe way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So how about your step-father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh he - he passed out th
rough booze in - booze got hold of him in the end and he - passed out quite happily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What year was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh no, he lasted 'til about the '30's, about the - yes, he lasted 'til about the - near enough - '28 - '28 I think it was, yes, round about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did he keep working in the docks all that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh he worked - 'til he - he worked in the docks to the end. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
You say he was out of work in the dock strike of 1912, was he ever out of work after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh he was never out of w
ork 'cos he was on the permanent staff of the - of the docks. With his - ability as an all round - crane driver you see. Hydraulic crane driver. But he could - he was very adaptable - at all types of cranes. He was considered a - a top driver but his only
 
downfall is - was the drink, off of it he - was good, but he could drink just as - he could drive just as good drunk or sober. He had - of course it - it was his life's work and - a crane - driving a crane becomes like a man with a hammer or chisel. They 
just know the touch and where and when and what.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Do you think then you got more from your mother in terms of you know your values?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well naturally we - I naturally - yes, I - my mother had an uphill battle, he wasn't a great asset, as a matter of 
fact when I went to work - my little income, then, as I started as a messenger boy in the docks at five bob a week and then - after the first year I got a stripe - good conduct stripe which brought me another shilling and - and - that money going into the
 
home, you take very little out of it in those days 'cos six bob in those days was six bob. And I think I only used to get a bob - a bob for the weekend expenditure out of it. But - outside of that I - that job I used to do - do little odd jobs of - when t
h
e colony of Yiddisher people started settling in Commercial Road, on a Friday nights you know they - from dusk on Friday they won't - do any - touch anything in the way of - work or anything, so - I - we had a little gang, I got a little gang of about - w
e
 were about four or five handed and we used to - clean and light their fires for - clearing - clean out their fires on Friday night and lay them and - light them and do the - the Saturday morning - go round Saturday morning and light 'em again. 'Course th
e
ir - their - religiously at weekend used to start from - dusk on - Friday - 'til - twenty-four hours later on Saturday. 'Cos their - their Saturday - their Saturday was their Sunday - their Sunday you see. That's why I say that you - as the years went on 
that's why - Petticoat Lane - the big market in Aldgate not far from us up the - Commercial Road, developed into a Jewish community because it was - Sunday - all Sunday you see.
