Oh I - I - I - it's only hopping in me infancy, I didn't take no - no - notice of it as I got older. Or nor did my mother because as growing up the responsibility was too big, and - then she was 
occupied with her own work to keep things going, 'cos she did - she did - office work in the City, to keep - make ends meet. 'Cos the step-father's money was - wasn't sufficient to keep the home going. And their top wage was only twenty-one bob a week.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
What would your mother say if another child hurt you, would she say hit him back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
What, oh my mother said if you're no - oh well my mother if I - you daren't go home crying in our house. No, be a - go out and have a battle. Oh yes, you had t
o - oh you had to - you had to take your own part in the East End in - in my kid days, I suppose it's - where you're getting the generation of these young terrorists today, it's the blood coming out. Like the fathers were. But - which you see a thing I do
n
't agree with because we - got to a time now that we're - all more or less - better civilized than we were. Or in better positions and comfort in life. But in the old days you - you - you - you - you had to defend yourself to - to get on, I mean if you we
n
t to a - a sort of a charity - charity tea at the local hall - if there was anything good like knocking about and somebody - somebody was grabbing it and - and you had to have a battle to get - get your share of it, if the - if the - teachers or whoever w
as looking after us weren't weren't around. Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How often would these charity teas take place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh only at - only at certain times. You might get one - you'd always get one round about Christmas. Either the - neighbours'd collect to
gether and - help the churches out whichever denominations they might be, or - or a certain - certain do - oh but you didn't - you didn't get a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was your mother or father ever a member of things like Christmas clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh we was always in Chri
stmas clubs. Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh well, you had to - you had to go in the Christmas club to make it a Christmas. You - well - we'd start off with that, you'd start off with that, I mean, where greengrocery was - terribly cheap I mean, you could always get y
o
ur greengrocery - didn't worry about that. But when - when it come to the turkey and the - and the - high living stuff, then - it was couple of bob a week put away and - and the family - likewise, members of the family, I used to - I used to put, as I got
 
on and I used to - religiously put - five bob a week away all the - all the year round. I'm talking about when I was in - I was in the twenties and - that's - that - five bob a week used to go into the local pubs loan club, and - which we'd share out abou
t a week before Christmas or - roughly a fortnight, well might be a fortnight or a week, whichever way - way - whichever way it pleased them, and that would - that would lay the table on for Christmas. That - that saved - oh my step-father, he was a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 nonentity}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
, he - he - he - he - he could never save any - anything, he - he's - the only thing he could save was lean up against the boozer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was your mother a member of anything like a boot club or a sick club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well, mother, yes, was always on the tally
, that's how we got - tally, that's how we got our - our clothes. Yes. Apart from sometimes she used to save a dollar a week I used to give her but - I think part of that - part of that went to pay the tallyman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did your step-father ever take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, I never had nothing to do much with me step-father, I know he was a drunk and I left him alone. He left me alone and I left him alone.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I wondered if he went to the races or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Yet funnily enough - funnily 
enough at - I was his foreman in the docks after - after - coming up from a messenger boy upwards and being on the same department as me I was his gaffer. So he had to behave himself. But when I saw at work he was getting beyond it through the - through t
h
e drink, which was his - which he couldn't do without, he was a living - he was a living alcoholic. He'd have it for breakfast, dinner and tea. And - you couldn't - never get it out of his system, I tried him out to - to dry him out once or twice but it w
as no use, it - he couldn't, it's been his - been his life and as I say he died of the - he was only about - he could only have been about forty-eight when he died, and - he was just hopeless.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 But you don't remember whether he went to races or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh they went nowhere, he only went to the docks to work and in the boozer, that was his - leave home, get down to the docks, before they - get - leave home about seven o'clock, get down before they shut, like they used to shut the dockside pubs, have a 
six o'clock - six to eight licence. All wayside dock pubs, as - well most of 'em who were near the dock gates, and he'd have his booze before he got in. Oh he's - he's breakfast was a - a pint of old and mild and - that was that. Even sandwiches - even sa
n
dwiches were - were cut for him to take regular for his midday snack, 'cos in those old days - up 'til about the twenties you only got half an hour's dinner in the - in the docks. It was only - just after the first world war that the - the hour's come in,
 to lengthen the - or might have been just before the - first world war, I'm - bit dubious of that, anyhow - the war - the first world war altered a lot of working conditions, in dockland and - and - and transport industry all round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have Bank Holidays before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, you had Bank - we had a - a Bank Holiday and - always one day was always sure of in the docks - an - an extra holiday was the King's birthday, that - docks closed on those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever go anywhere on those days?
