\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have a bike before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Yes, because I had the first bike ride soon after I left school, to Southen
d, midnight bike ride, we was about - I was about thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Who would you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 And that was - and that's - that was a good -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you go with friends from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, I always used to meet with the older boys in the turning funni
ly enough. Being a - an - a delicate - developing all round athlete, I used to - always seem to be connected with the - boys two or three years older than myself. And never got on a lot with boys - kids of me own age - why I don't know because they - they
 weren't quick off the mark or - might be me a bit more exceptional but - which I was more or less a - a - always up looking to the older side to mix with them, always wanted to get on their level, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You said you did high diving?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh alway
s at the Peoples Palace baths yes. Up at the old Peoples Palace baths we used to - hold our competitions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What other kinds of sports did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, I played - I was - I was good at amateur - good amateur football, I played for old - Walthamstow Grange. A {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 league on Saturdays. After the first world war of course. In the Army I represented the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 battalion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  and the - and the - and the brigade, I was - I was always a cert in that team. And - when I come out the Army I played for the fir
m, Port of London Authority, and - and to earn a few bob we used to play Sunday morning football, you got a - you got a few bob for playing Sunday morning football - 'cos you had to keep that - play under - play under another name 'cos - if the - Amateur 
- Amateur Association found out you was banned, for life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 That's still true now isn't it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - no, the bans off now, they - they've recognised Sunday football which a thing they should have done in the old days, because - you used to work Satu
rdays so what chance did you have. You got one Saturday off in three. If you was on the staff of the P.L.A. or perhaps if you were on a small department you got one a fortnight. Well it was - you used to work - just like an ordinary day. 'Til the - 'til t
he - about - after the - again - all these things after the first world war. The docks - went from eight 'til twelve. And now I - I think that they don't open on Saturdays at all, I'm not sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Going back to Christmas Day, would you have any relatives 
round on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, you'd always have a do, oh yes, so somebody - you'd always have somebody turning up - you - you know, more or less were turning up. But in the evening you never knew who was going to turn up. Because it used to be an o
pen house on - on - over the Christmas. It was - just open - from Christmas Eve to Boxing night when you - continued to Boxing Day night, you never know who's going to turn up. And more or less the - the - you had to sharpen up because - if you didn't sha
r
p - go to your work the day after - after Boxing Day - you - you were - in for stripes off of whoever - whoever you - your employer was. But in the docks we used to have a staff, being on the staff there - we had an arrangement on the - your own staff, de
p
artmentally - some'd have the day off before Christmas, Christmas Eve, and some would have the day off after. Well knowing my family I always used to have the day off after. Because I knew there was - would be parcel - parcel of my job to do all the clear
ing up - if we'd have a bit of a do. In other words, take the empties back and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have any relatives living in the neighbourhood in Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh - no, no relatives no, we you - we were - my eldest brother, he lived at 
- well away on the other side of the water, we never knew his address 'cos he - family row with the - his wife and mother and - they never spoke for years. The only one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you were very young though I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, I'm talking about after the fi
rst world war. And of course the - in the young days in Wapping as I say we had - all the family were - were in service, me second brother was - was a - away in the home. And as I said previously put there by the old man - the old man's solicitor in the C
ity. And my eldest brother always lived in - on the public house where he was working, 'cos he was always a - assistant manager or a manager or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would they come round for Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 All according. All according. Though you'd see some of 'em 
- part, it's all according how their duties went you see, 'cos service in those - those days was just like - they had just as good a party where they're - in their own big households as they - coming home to - to what they was used to at home, see. And mo
re or less we relied upon them to bring something home for making a bit of a do, see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about birthdays, would they be special as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh, you talk about that, might get a card. It - it was just birthday birthday but as you got older you sor
t of - found the trend of social life and when you got a - more on - on your feet and made friends of course you started - recognising birthdays and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you have presents and things like that when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 But - 
I never used to leave my mother out, I always used to send her a card. Well, no, well it - it - it - it didn't run to it. Your wages - your wages didn't allow you to - yet things were cheap, you always wanted something good but you couldn't get it because
 you hadn't got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you wouldn't have anything like a birthday party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh you would, you'd have a - yes, you'd have a birthday party - amongst your pals if it's your birthday then - your - if it was your church club pals or your pals - who you 
mixed with, boys and girls, and you arrange a bit of a party at home, but then you didn't have the accommodation because the rooms were so small. I mean - this room here that you're sitting in here, well take the whole of it. That would cover the whole of
 
the house from front to back. And in that - in that front of the - in that - space that we - as we've got here - there'd be one, two, three, four and a scullery, five - five bits. So you can quite see how much bigger rooms were. Once you got a piano in a 
room, we had a piano - and once you got that in the room it took up so much space.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have a piano in the house in Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes, we always had a piano, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Who played the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Nobody. It was only - it was the right thin
g that you had to be - it was the right thing to have a piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did anybody play a musical instrument in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well the idea in - the idea of - of a piano was to - to - to teach my young - sister, well the - the child - the eldest girl of 
the - mother's second marriage, my step-sister as you'd say. And - she never took to it. I was more successful than her, teaching myself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
When you had Christmas dinners and things like that would people play the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh well you always - now 
that was when - that's when piano players were diamonds you see. You - if you had a piano then you had to go all - all out planning who you was going to smuggle for Christmas you see. And - and you generally found - unless he was a close friend, you were 
a
ll right, but if you was banking on a stranger - you - he - he'd say, well yes and no, so you used to make arrangements with two or three. To be sure of one, coming round for part of the time. But of course, then again, your gramaphone - the old gramaphon
e, the old - the old His Master's Voice, that used to be the - that used to be the saver, 'cos you see you'd go -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You had one of those in Wapping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh - no, no, no. No, not in Wapping, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How about Stepney?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh Stepney we had a go - a -
 a gramaphone. Now, we had a music box in Wapping. Roller. A roller - a - a roller thing. That's all we had there, in the - in the way of music.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Only me. Only me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you give performances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I u
sed to do - any church does, you know, have a - well if they - put of a bit of a - a doe on, a concert and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You would never sing in the home though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
And - oh well we had a bit of do you would always give a song. Oh yes. My - my ballads was what my mother used to like, was - the - the Irish ditties. Mother McCree and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did she sing at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
And - oh, she could warble. Oh yes. Yes. The old lady, she could sing a good - good number.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What would your mother and step-father think of you
 speaking when grown ups were talking?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well my step-father as I said before, never come into our family, he wasn't recognised by 'em, somehow or the other - he was just a - he was - termed old Bill. Well that - he never proved himself, that's why, b
ecause we were an hard working family, and my mother had made a mistake and - and knew it and couldn't get out of it, that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
What did your mother think of you speaking when grown ups were talking, what did she think about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, well - as a child - as a child you weren't allowed, you weren't allowed in the elders conversation, I can quite remember that. You was always told to - get. But - as you - as I say - the first world war altered the w
hole complex of - everything. Where a young person was concerned. You went away a boy and come back a man. That was the answer. See, you went away a boy, I went away - at seventeen and come back when I was about twenty. See? I never had one leave, 'cos yo
u - they were - well they were so short of men, you never had a leave. I mean, once you got over to France and there you were. Otherwise you come back alive or you was buried over there, one out the two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you were little what did your mother think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well that never allowed in our house. No. No. Even I've - I've heard my mother - and - being - as we were, always brought up churchy - I told her of it. And - the telling her - telling of it to her I think done - hurt her more than - any
thing else. 'Course it was natural in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East End{\*\xmlclose}
 I mean, it was a - a - it was a - a sort of a - everyday language. I mean you never - some people - some men in the docks in my young days could never speak without - without - bad words in every sentence.
 The so and so, so and so and that's so and so so and so, of course - but there was always a bad word there. A b or an f always seemed to float all - all through the moon or - it was there. And I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would your mother punish you in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I - I 
was very much - oh no, no, not when we - as - as children, we never used it. Never knew it. We never knew it in the house, it wasn't allowed. As I say, if it was ever said and as I say as a kid I can remember it being once when - the step-father and mothe
r
, she was having a go at him - and I had to tell her about her bad language of - of - about her bad language because - being a choirboy I didn't like it. And from then on I don't think I ever heard her use a bad word, while we were in the house, but she c
ould Lord Mayor if she went off, oh she was a real cockney. Oh yes, she could go a - could go off the deep end with the best of 'em.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
What would happen if you did something your mother disapproved of when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh you didn't. I didn't. I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You wouldn't get punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, no. If I was ever - whatever venture I was going in I always confided in my mother. If I wanted to stay our - out - our time for getting in at nights was nine o'clock. We want to stay out 'til ten she gen
erally liked you to say so. Because in those days as I say that - well it was - every man for himself - girls - never out after dark. Never. Never. Not because of the - men of the neighbourhood were bad, but being Stepney - and - more or less a seaside - 
a
 - a - a shipping port, you never - they - you never know in the main roads who you - who they were meeting. But as I say we had no trouble with girls, there was only - one girl, my youngest step-sister, and - she was always a mother's girl, where you saw
 one you saw the other. And she got married very young, so - she had a - she had a man ; all to herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you can't remember being punished for being in late or anything like that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh never. No, no, no, no. Oh no. Oh no, my - we - we - as I say
 that - you see - events in my young age - weren't the same as today as when you say punish, because - oh - there was always a war on. You see, and I was coming fifteen there was a war on. Oh I was just coming like on a messenger boy on the docks, bang, h
e
re comes the war. So gradually I mean - the whole of the - domestic system - changes. There's less of everything for everybody. Things were hard to get. The black market was super. The cleverer you were at - at - fiddling, the better you were. Everybody w
as at it. So in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 consequence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
 was you see - my young life was - brought up - my teenage - well out of me teenage into me working age, was war. I only had a fair chance at work for a couple of years before I was in the - in the - in the Army. And which I - I c
ome out when I was around about twenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you started as a messenger in the docks what were your hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh then - seven o'clock turn or eight o'clock turn. 'Til five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You were a messenger up until the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You did seven
 o'clock you were off at four o'clock. If you did eight o'clock you was off at five o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have any half days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No half days, no, you got - when we worked there as I say we used to - Saturday was a full day. You get one - if there was three messenger boys you get one in three. Or perhaps two in three, all according how many - how may ships was in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What exactly was involved in messenger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh running from - if there was two in a department, one would have the City run. There was no posting done. Messengers done - hand delivered all the letters themselves and - by walking from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} dock and touring the City with the letters like a postman with 'em. So if you was on the City run you'd have that for a week. And you'd come back on 
- working in the department. Department would be - one - one department to another, round the dock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You did that 'til you went in the Army, then you came out of the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When I come out the Army, 'course I was old enough to go on the staff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well assistant foreman then. Assistant to foreman. Well that's called junior assistant foreman. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 'T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 il you was twenty-one, 'cos you was under age, so I was a junior assistant 'til I was twenty-one, and I automatically become an assistant foreman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you become a foreman eventually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh no I never stayed long enough in the P.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
.A., I - I - took an exam and graduated to - to being what they call a - on the sorting staff, a sampler, I graduated to - after the exam you became a 
sampler, on the sorting staff. That means that you was a - passed examining tin - tinned food and - another one was sugar grading, then sugar grading, and - general - general observation of - of damage. Damage to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 This was still in the docks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 In the docks. That was the grade I had that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So how old were you when you took your exam to become a sampler?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh well, you didn't - you - that - that - that - they - they - then - yes, that was after the - after I returned from - military servic
e. Well then - you go - you go up to the - head office of the Port of London Authority and there you've got a board of - board of experts, all foremen from the staff of - of the - senior foremen from the staff of the Authority, who sit round in a - egg sh
a
ped table and you take up your position - in the middle, facing the Chairman of the Board. And any member who's about - generally about - let's see, how many was there there, oh there's about of 'em, yes, about eight, eight there was, and - they ask you t
h
e - the Chairman asks you what you - you wish to become a sampler? You say, yes sir. And he said, well what commodities do you think that you - are expert in and have - have - have had sufficient knowledge and experience - of what cargoes? In particular? 
A
nd then write - ring - ring off what you think that you know - particular - what particular - cargoes or goods you know and all the - all the things that - the - history attached to them like - oh, where it's grown and the port of origin, where it was shi
p
ped and all that sort of thing. And so you rattle off whatever - class of - goods that you think you're expert in and - that puts you up to sample see. Say for instance you say that you know the tin game, they chuck you a tin of - sardines or a tin of som
e
 whatever it might be and say, well - what's up with that, how would you classify that? See? Pass it to you. Well you could see that it was a firm - a good tin. The label, printing was all clean and nice. No slight rust or was clear of all slight rust or 
-
 any affect at all. Oh no, what have I - what have I got to look for, there's something I've got to look for. It's not blown, it shows no signs of part being blown. It shows no signs of being collapsed, that's dented. I've got to - now I've got to look fo
r
 a pierce. Yes. So you go and take your tin, you survey it, and then you - if the contents is - meat or fish - if there's a leak of any sort you'll hear a plonk-plonk. And if it's juicy and got liquor in it of any sort, it could be tinned fruit, you'll he
a
r a suckle-suckle see. So if you get a plonk-plonk you know you've got a pierce so you search for the hole and - the expert has put a - has put a small hole with a nail, hammered a nail under the flange in the tin, ordinary tin has got a flange round it y
o
u know. And he's pierced it with a - just a - a small nail called a tee-bright, so if you turn it over and it's got any substance in it, liquid at all then you find that'll - come out. See? That's what they call - is - that's graduated as pierced, and - t
h
en - all tinned - all tinned goods you see, that come into the Port of London, are subject to being inspected by the Port Sanitary Officer. Who - if on a - on a percentage examination, sometimes you have a - a cargo - if there's a hundred cases he'll have
 three opened or five, if there was a thousand cases he might have ten. Seven or ten. And have a look at 'em. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 
If he's satisfied with those - those cases being picked from all over the ranged of the thousand cases, some cases- are numbered and some not, but 
any case from anywhere well he'll pick out himself, in a stacked pile, one from there, one from there, one from there, and he'll say, I'll come and view them tomorrow morning, and before he goes he'll mark 'em, so he should know - then he knows that they'
re the right cases. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
But any case - he had no fear of the - of any - intimidation in any way because - the P.L.A. staff worked hand in glove with all authorities, never mind who they are, especially the customers. They all worked hand in hand, sort of a - a 
brotherhood, whatever happens between - this - this - two - or any knowledge, was passed from one to the other automatically so - theres really no - no - there's no outlet for - trying anything on. It don't come off.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How long did you work as a sampler for?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh I stayed in the P.L.A. and I - 'til 1926, and then I - then I resigned. I left P.L.A. to go - to go into - to - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 freelancing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  in shipping. Jobs was going - jobs were - well - there was vacancies in one or two shipping lines as I was tipped o
ff about, 'cos the wages of the Port of London Authority for staff were very small, very meager. Very meagre. You only rose - you only rose by two bob a year, to come to your top rank.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What were you getting when you were a messenger boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Five bob. And shilling for the stripe. Six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What were you getting when you were a junior assistant foreman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Twelve bob. Rising - rising to - eighteen bob, then you stopped. 'Til you was twenty-one, then you come on a full assistant's wages. You come from a junior assistant to the - then you come on to twenty-two or three bob a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have holidays with pay with these jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes. Yes. You always got a fortnight's holiday. Fortnight's holiday when you got - went on the staff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 And you
 say you gave the money you got when you first started work to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
My mother was always my saver, she was my bank. Well that was the only way we - we succeeded. We couldn't get any money off the old man because he - what - he give his weekly
 - penance up out of his wages which was no more than - if he done a bit of overtime - never - never - big but - he never give up nor more than - to my knowledge, the whole of the time, 'course booze was very cheap in those days, a pint was only - cheap w
as tuppence - tuppence ha'penny and the best was threepence. So - he'd keep his beer money and give the rest up to the - up to - up to the - up to mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Did you think your five shillings a week and your twelve shillings a week was a fair wage for those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, it wasn't. Not for what you did. No. How comes -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Not even with the cost of living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well then - then it was below - below average for the cost of living. I mean you take a boy running his - from seven o'clock in the morning 'ti
l four o'clock in the afternoon, and you didn't get a lot of sitting downtime, there was always something to do, if you'd finished your run and come back to your department, you finished your City job and come back to your department - you had to get prep
a
red for your other City run at two o'clock in the afternoon, which you could take you up to five o'clock by the time you finished. The only time - chance you had of - swining is if you'd got a light - a light afternoon do, and your mate on the next depart
m
ent who you arranged to meet, who you'd met in the morning, or two or three if you had met in the morning, we generally used to make our meeting place outside the Mint. On Tower Hill. You know the Mint? Well - you know the lake in front there, well that's
 
where we used to meet to make - to make our marking time and swap letters, that means to say - if I had - nearly all merchants in the City, so if I had a batch of letters for the - that merchant or two or three, and he had two or three so we used to swap 
t
o shorten the journey. So - say he was - this one - we used to make our sorting office up there, keep on - one keeping doggo and two sorting see. Sort the letters on the list there, to shorten our run. So instead of our run - taking us - all the morning, 
i
t would only take us an hour, because you'd do the Cannon Street area, I do - you do Eastcheap and Cannon Street, and I'd do the other part of the City, Basing or wherever it might - Basinghall and all round there, so we used to divide the City up into th
r
ee, so that we shorten our journey, so that we were all finished hours before, so instead of getting back as we was - always had to - get back at dinner time at twelve o'clock - and we used to set off about half past eight, quarter to nine, we'd be finish
ed here about ten o'clock. See? So we used to go then in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Tower{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Gardens{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and sit it out. See?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How did you like the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Or go round the Tower. That's why I know the Tower in and out so well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you enjoy the work as a messenger boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 W
ell - of course you enjoyed it, the simple reason that - you - you had a uniform which you was proud of, which I was, and it had to be cleaned and done every night, gaiters and all that sort of thing. But you always looked - you used to - we always used t
o look with a bit of envy on the Post Office boys you see, because they were Government, but of course, we used to consider ourself Government being the Port of London Authority, we considered ourself as good as them. But - they had bikes and we didn't.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How did the employers treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh, well they were only the working class the same as us. Oh we were their boys and that was that, so long as you behaved yourself and - and if you come from good homes as - as I had come from a good home where it's
 very strict - yes, sir - yes sir to everybody, it had to be yes sir, never mind who it was. If it was only a - a - if he's only - only left the messengers and took up a junior assistanceship he was your mate one week and he was a junior assistant the nex
t
, and he was on the staff and you was on the department, you still had to give him a certain amount of - a certain amount of winks if not - you didn't call him sir but - you couldn't treat him on the level you know but it was all - all very decorum like t
hat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever have any part time jobs before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
I told you like light the Yiddisher fires Saturday - Friday nights. Friday. I had me round and me gang. They used to - that was enough part time
 for me. I never tried a paper round. You know, some of me mates had a paper round. That was too bad, getting up at five in the morning to - to - do that for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How long would this job on the Friday nights take, would it be all night?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh it's up 
to you what sort of night you had. Now some Jews houses you don't - you'd have the kitchen, you'd have the front room, and you might have a couple of bedrooms to do. You see. Well they - they was always - always well-to-do Jews, like they - they - they - 
t
hey had some - they had some poppy, and - they used to see that you was well treated so you was always - the money was always left, you never had to dispute over money. 'Cos they always say - they'd always say to you - well there was always a - a tanner w
a
s a lot of money those days you see, tanner a house was a lot of money, that was more than - more than you got if you was hard working, that's more than you could earn for a week's wages, if you had a good - but the only way to do it again was to form it 
into a gang, see. As I say, I had four or five working for me, I collected these houses - through my mother because she knew - she was very friendly with - a - a - a Jew - Mr Harris in Houndsditch, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 jeweller}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 , had a shop. It was where - the shop where the - the - he owned is where the - the - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Sidney Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 gang broke into. Yes. My mother worked within that shp - where they - they burgled to make their break through, yes, she was clean - she used to be cleaner for them. Well it was through - him - being a - E
nglish Jew and having the jewelers - that he connected me - connected her with all these - well-to-do Jews who lived in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Commercial Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 then. And they're nearly all - in different - trades, furs, tailoring or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 jewellery}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  or whatever it might be. 'Cos - y
ou never found a Yiddisher - a Yiddish - a Yiddisher pick worker on the road or a - or a - or one in the docks come to that. They're all luxury trade workers. Never - never any - never any muscle work for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So how many houses a night would you do do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
We used to do, with the gang, we used to do - we'd do about twenty houses. And - well we'd have so many Motzers, they always used to leave a packet of Motzers, so we had so many Mot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 ers that - that we used to - take them to a certain - 
to people who liked them and - and copped up a penny or tuppence or threepence off of them, according to the size of the packet. So we - we picked up both ways. My mother liked mot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 ers so I used to take a packet home every week to her. She liked them with 
a - a bit of cheese, butter and cheese, and so did some of the others, so - some of her mates like 'em I never earnt so much because she used to take two or three packets off me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you give the money to your mother that you earnt when you were doin
g these things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Mm. My mother was my banker all me life. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you come into contact with the people you were doing it for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
What, with the Jews? No, you - they were generally - generally - when we went round they were generally at syn
agogue. And they began to know you, you see, they leave a key in a certain spot for you. Or if not they'd leave the - they leave the shicksa servants, shicksa, the - the - I mean the gentile, that's - our - our people who were doing the cleaning, they lea
ve them on duty to open the door for you. Well, nearly always had an English girl servant. To look after the kids or - or be head - head bottle - head bottle - pusher and - doings for the - for the household.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you find this kind of work altered your attitude to school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, it didn't take you no time did it. Take no time, the time the - time you stepped in, and if the - the girl in the house was one of our own - she used to help out. We was only then about I suppose - about twelve. Twelve
 or - yes, about twelve or thirteen. And if she was a young 'un, she was young herself they generally used to take the young school girls the Jews, if she was only fourteen or fifteen you generally - found that she was connected with one of your schools. 
Y
ou knew her. And she was only taking the job for the - living with the - with the Jews for the simple reason - the - family was outgrowing their capacity at home. So they took a job with the Jews so she could have a - live - live out from home. Or in othe
r words get off of the family budget.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 How long did you do the job freelance in the shipping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 In the shipping? Up 'til the - up to the start of the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 The second world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Second world war. Yes. Then I - then I - volunteered for other ports, and - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Port{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London Authority Executives{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - formed a board and we had to go before them, about twenty of us, we were termed then - then - termed then as - ship's clerks. And true enough who was sitting on the board was a couple of my old guv'nors,
 who I'd served with - while I was a member of the P.L.A. Oh they said, we've got - we've no need - to worry our head about qualifications here, Bill'll tell us everything, 'cos most of the men who - who went, the twenty of us, ships clerks, about twenty 
I
 think there was, yes, and I was able to say that we were all qualified ships clerks, the - knew their business from top to bottom. All come from reputable stevedore firm. And cargo superintending firms who knew - what was what about shipping. So the poin
t was that we was right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So how long did you do that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No - and that was - that was start of the second world war. When everybody was called up. Oh those under age - military age had to go in the Army from the docks, 'cos the docks was bombed
, there was no work. Those of military age had to go into the - into the - the - shipping side of the pioneering - Royal Engineers, to handle ships, and - to do the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 car going}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  and unloading and all that of ships. And - us who were over military age - I was 
because I had served in the first world war then, I was about forty years old. And we went - volunteered to freelance - and travel round other ports - to do the clerical work in the discharge of loading the cargoes of - whatever port we could get the ship
s in. So we were a sort of a - a wandering band.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 You did that in the second war did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
The second world war, that's what we're doing, well when we got to - we've been - we done all the Welsh coast - and - and - and been to Milford Haven and don
e all the Welsh coast, that's right - Cardiff, Swansea, and - and Barry, Barry was timber. And then - we - during the - there was - heavy losses then in shipping with the submarines - and we were called back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Then when we got back to London they 
give us a - two or three days rest, two or three days rest and told us to - report again - to - a Labour Exchange over at - at - Rotherhithe, 'cos we were nearly all Surrey Dock - all Surrey Dock ship's clerks. And then they asked for volunteers for 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Well me being bombed out, we were bombed out then - had no home. I was only too pleased to - to say that - put me in. See. When I said - when I said, put me in, the same fellow again - who was in charge, one of my old guv'nors, said, I was waiting for 
that, right, you're in charge of the party again. So then I had - another - crew - to take up to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. I was never in charge of 'em - we only - only thing was that - when I got to these port places where there was the Director of the - where the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 Minister}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
 of Labour and shipping - consulted me, I had to - he had to tell me what he wanted - what he required and then I had to say to him, well there's your man, and ask - ask the man would he - well that was agreed amongst us that they'd see - we'd accept anyt
hing that we had to do, so there was no saying, I don't want that. But - there was a certain - certain amount of comradeship is - I want to stick with you Bill. Or I want to stick with you Fred, or you'll partner me, because it was digs all the time. And 
o
f course, wherever you go where men are, especially in the working classes, you'll always find that there's - a little - a little class grade you know. Well I was a very particular sort fellow, I was - always have all me life, so - kept up - kept - kept u
p smart.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever belong to any trade union organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh yes, you definitely had to in our game. You - you - you didn't get any work unless you was a trade union - a trades union member. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When did you join the trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh you - you had to, I was in the trade union as soon as I was - soon as I went on the staff of the P.L.A., 1916. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What union was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Transport and General Workers Union. Then it was the Dock - Dock and - Dock - Dock and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Riverside{\*\xmlclose} - Dock and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Riverside{\*\xmlclose} staff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you take part in any of the activities of the trade union movement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
I was a delegate for me branch. Yes, I was delegate for me branch of the - of the - I - over at Surrey Docks. Yes, oh yes, you had to hold your ticket, you - they - you - when you were a - when you - not so much when you was an employee of the - of the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Port{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}London Authority{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, but they did expect you to be a member of the staff associations. Yes we had a lot of black 'uns who weren't members of the Sta
ff Association, but that was only more or less meanness, it wasn't their - it wasn't their views, it was was just the case that they didn't part - like parting with their bob a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you feel there was a division between employers and workers in those days?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No. No, we - you - sometimes - in the - in the Port of London you got - what they call - superintendants, assistant superintendants, they were the head dicks, then you got your warehousekeepers and assistant warehousekeepers, they were dep
artmentally - well sometimes you got a - an awkward Johnny, but if he was awkward and he was a - he wasn't playing - playing ball or tried to be the - the major domo of the job then you made things bloody awkward for him, you see, so - it was really in hi
s interest - if he - he became - a sort of father of the staff, he'd have everybody working for him. But if he didn't - then he'd have a - the bright lads'd get to work and - make things awkward for him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you say there was a great division between
 trained craftsmen and other workers in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Yes, well - that happen - that - that - that - that stood out a mile in the P.L.A. They had a major staff - which were - were - were the - ledger staff and the - and the - and the warehousekeeping s
taff, the warehousekeepers, your guv'nors, they were all on the major staff, and we foremen etc. were all on the minor staff. You see. And - there was a - that distinction between the two in the P.L.A. that - that - there was always a bit of an eyesore, b
e
cause you had to work with each other so much close in hand that - that the foremen as they were more experienced men, being out with the cargoes and the ships all day, sort of had to tell the - the clerical side who were the major staff to - the ledger s
t
aff more or less you could call them, ledgers, because - the majority of the clerical work - held the - housing of the cargoes and the delivery of the cargoes was the foremen's staff which their returns had to be sent to the ledger staff, so you were - mo
r
e or less always be holden to the ledger staff to sort of look up - because they called themselves the major staff. And they were those - they were - they knew less about the job because if there was any explanation to be done in the way of - complaints a
b
out cargoes, rents and any other thing, it all come back to the foreman. He had to answer it, and send his reply to the major staff and ledger staff who would have - pass it - pass his - his replies up to the - the powers that be. So - it was just a - a c
lass distinction. You had to be a public schoolboy to get on the major staff. Whereas the ordinary - schoolboy, the ordinary - local schoolboy was on the minor staff, that was the difference. One -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you serve an apprenticeship or training period for any of your jobs?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well your messenger boy, that was your training see. Yes. Of course before you got on the staff, on the foreman's staff, you had to pass a - sit-down exam - at a City of London College to - go on the foreman's staff, from a messen
ger boy to the foreman's staff. If you passed you went on the foremen's staff, if you failed you went on the labour staff. See? On the cargo side see. But if you passed, so - a lot of the busy - used to fail because - down on the labouring staff - you cou
ld earn more money. But of course you weren't on a pension. Where if you got on the foremen's staff - your money was smaller, your overtime was smaller, but you were pensionable, and you got more holidays. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you say that full time work changed your attitude to life in any way?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh - that's all you was looking for from a kid, leaving school and getting to work, to earn a few bob. Oh yes. Oh that was the - you were dying for the day of leaving school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have any regrets about your education afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - not - looking at the angle today, this is years later to talk about - there was a vast difference, vast difference. I mean, if you went to a - church school in my day you'd had it, you were religiously filled. And if
 you went to an L.C.C. school - it was quite different, but you didn't get the range that they get today. I mean - it's true in the - in the - in the - you - you had that break of carpentry and - a bit of - tin work, but - that was the only - other thing,
 after you leave - left school, 'cos after I left school - and I entered the P.L.A., I had to - my mother insisted upon me continuing in night school which I did. Which I did for a couple of years, continue night school and the nearest - L.C.C. school.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What did you do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well, studied up for the - studied up for the exam, for the - for the - messenger boy's exam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Would you have stayed longer at school if you'd have had the opportunity do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. No, you wanted money. No. Bec
ause your - your parents - your parents didn't want you - they wanted you out soon as they could get. Matter of fact - I - I had left school, the summer holidays come along - and I - started me job during the summer holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Do you think you benefited from attending school though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No, no, in those days you was out - you - you - education you didn't put - you didn't put education first as they do today. You - you was out earn - you - you - you - what you wanted was money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did your mother show much interest in your school work though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes, definitely. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did she ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh yes, she always - yet she couldn't read - read - read or write. She -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would you have any books or things like that in the house when you were young?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Only what you bought home yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Your parents didn't have any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, no, no. No. They couldn't read or write.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would they ever play any games with you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Games? Well they didn't know much 
about that - didn't know - didn't know how to play cards even.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would they ever visit the school, your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Only if you was in trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you ever in trouble at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever get punished or anything like that at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, I was Captain of the - was Captain of me school - school cricket team.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What kind of punishments did the teachers give to the other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh always got the cane. But - they never used it - unless you was - unless you was a real bad 'un. And if you was a real bad 'un they generally tried to get rid of him. Because you was a - a bad influence on -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did they expel you or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well - they couldn't do that but they used to try and do - the teacher on his pat would try
 and do what he could with the parents, the headmaster'd - ask the parent to go up to the school and would have a chat, and find out - try and find out where the trouble was, but it was generally that the - the - unless the parent was interested, they nev
e
r troubled. You - it was just a - a mere of a - it was whatever your family was you were. You see. The - the whole of the - the whole of the individual developed - developed round the family life. It it was a bad family it was a bad family. If it was a go
od family -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you were lucky really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
And my mother always believed in - in - in - in - that you got to be - of course, that breeding come from us, from the - my - my father - being a City man, a City - contractor you see, and my mother always mi
xing with the gentry during her - experience in the City like, with the - father's insurance or the different companies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did your mother allow you to play with anyone you liked when you were young?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh - free agent. - Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What would she think if you got dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh well, I always - you was always forced to keep yourself clean. Oh yes, she wouldn't allow you to go to bed dirty either. Well you - the - the - you never had had to be told where our family was concerned. 
There was the - there was your - your soap and your bowl and - that's it, get on with it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have any hobbies when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
My - my hobby was - well - at school - one - one thing that used to interest - carpentry used to interes
t me a lot, I used to like that a bit, I used to like making things, but the thing that did interest me was - one of our teachers was - a map of India. So you get - you get cardboard, see, or - or - or - just slightly thick paper, and you cut out a design
 
of India, then you paint in all the provinces in different colours and - sort of leave a little space so that you could print the name of 'em and all that and - that used to interest me. Anything - anything with a pen - 'cos I - I developed into a good pe
n man, which I - well - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 'cos}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
 - I was a - a good pen man, and still am today, and - anything in - with the pen, that interested me. Carpentry, to a certain extent, but no. I was always - I always wanted to become an artist. Always wanted to become an artist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did your parents give you pocket money in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well that's all according how things went along - on at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So it wasn't a regular thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No. No. If you - if you needed you got. If you needed - if you needed and it was - anyt
hing you got, but in those days you didn't - as long as you had a bellyful of grub - you had - and you had ha'penny - you earnt your ha'pennies, ha'pennies and pennies for toffees, 'cos you'd always go - go - to in and get a ha'porth of toffee. Farthingsw
orth you'd get three or four pieces, and a ha'porth - ha'porth you get - a bit and for - if you had a penn'orth you'd get half a slab. Oh yes, cheap as - sweets were very cheap. 'Course all - all loose you know. All loose sugar sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you have any pets or things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Ay? Oh yes, I had a - I had a dog. I was very fond of dogs. I had a dog, Nell For years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Did you ever go to any theatres or concerts or things like that while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Only - no, I was out at wor
k then, no, the only - we went to - well any local concert you know that was in - for - any church concert, but - my step-father did - under protest from my mother, more or less keep him out the pubs, I think it was, used to take me to the old Paragon, th
e old Shoreditch, walk all the way, when we lived in Wapping that was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was that music hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Music hall. Up the old Shoreditch - Shoreditch, and - if we didn't go there then we went to the Paragon in Mile End Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were there any cinemas around in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No. Them - the cinemas - first cinema - I can remember starting was the ha'penny - ha'penny Silver Land - in Commercial Road, that's where the - the big giants now who own the - own the big cinemas over the water and the - and the 
- the - cinemas - the - two brothers I think they were, they started the ha'penny Silver Land in Commercial Road, right next door to - right opposite Watney Street, in Commercial Road. Ha'penny - it used to cost you on - twelve o'clock - eleven o'clock - 
eleven o'clock 'til about - two o'clock - two or three o'clock in the - in - on - on - Saturdays. And then - then the prices of the cinemas in the evening used to be - top deck threepence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Can you remember when you were at church were you a member of a
ny temperance club or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh well, they're always temperance then in the church }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 goers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 . Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were there temperance clubs around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well there was a lot of temperance clubs around in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you a member?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. No, no, I only a member of me church club. I never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you ever in any youth club or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Oh well that was your church club. That was your church club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Ay? No. No, we - well, Christmas time, yes. High times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Were you taught to say your prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Up to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever have family prayers,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well you used to say 'em silently I think. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. My mother never belie
ved in that, she had a - a rigid rule, she said, the house of prayer is the church. As long as you keep - lead a good life and say your - say your own prayers - thats good enough. As long as you attend your church when you can when you're working, when yo
u can and when you want when you're working but as a child yes, you've got to go to your church and your Sunday school. That was her ruling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Another thing about your mother and step-father, you say that they .....

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Step-father never come into it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
You said that they weren't really interested politically, except something about Anthony Wedgewood Benn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Oh that was in Wapping, that was when Anthony Wedgewood Benn put up as the first Liberal - Liberal M.P. - in Wapping. Oh yes, we were all fo
r him because - he was the - the first one outside - we knew outside the Conservative 'erbs. The - land - land owning class you know. And Wedgewood Benn come out to look after the poor. Same as his father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 So you do you think your mother and step-fath
er were pro-Liberal then in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Well he was a bloke - he was a bloke - well politics, they - they didn't know the difference between Conservative, Labour or Liberal see. Though of course there was no - no Labour party, it was Conservative and
 Liberal then. And - you might got a sole independent. The Labour party only come into prominence just before - round about - round about 19 - round - round about the - yes - two - two or three years before the first world war when they started showing st
rength. But they sowed great strength after the first world war, through the unions. The - the unions started building the Labour party, as a matter of fact the unions built the Labour party. The unions are Labour - are - are the Labour party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Do you know whether your step-father voted before the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
He - step-father never come into our life at home, he was a - he - he - he wasn't recognised by me, you see. And - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I suppose your mother wouldn't have the vote then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Well no, women d
idn't have a vote, and - if you - you keep on bringing this step-father business in, if it did he'd vote for a pint - if a bloke offered him a pint he'd vote for that bloke. He was a good fellow. Politics, we weren't - the working class in -y day were not
 politic minded. If the local - if your local agent was your - your - your - your local member was coming to be - was your landlord, or connected with it, and he - you voted for him. You -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would this apply to you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No. No, it
 didn't because when I left school I went into the docks and I become very Labour minded. And I was a - a - a Labour - a Labour worker from - soon after I left the messengers. I used to sell the - the union - small pamphlet then or give it away at meeting
s and whatever it might be. I have been Labour all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 When you left school did you still go to Sunday school or church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Church. I kept up the - always kept up me church. When we moved from Wapping to Stepney.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 What about Sunday school, did you keep that up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Not - well not - not - 'cos I was working then, no, we didn't do Sunday school. But we would have a - according to what all the - the boys do - did - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4592392\charrsid5717858 we\rquote d
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858  either go to church Saturday - Sunday morning, or - or evening, whicheve
r - whichever one the vicar wanted us to do, if he wanted us to swell - if he - if - if he was busy Sunday mornings with weddings - we'd go in the evenings. And of course then - the - the - if we had a good - good clergyman he was our skipper. We relied u
pon him. Same as we had a - we used to consider the - a doctor - as a great friend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
Would your mother ever go out on her own anywhere or would she be too busy working and then just relaxing after work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 I can never remember my mother taking a holi
day. Going on holiday. Is when - as when one of us has been able to - to - send her away with - with - with the others. No, she never - outside of hopping I don't think my mother ever had a holiday 'til we got older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would she ever go out in the evenings on her own anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 
No. No, no. Was the - very seldom, very seldom you'd ever - unless - them four wheels was about, motoring was being - was - coming to its eight then, after the first world war, and onwards, we - my - my brother, second brothe
r, Ted, he had a - bought a little - Austin 7 then when they were the rage, and - one of my sister's husbands, he was a chauffeur, so she used to get occasional rides from the - from the relatives you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6173087 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 Would she have many friends come round to visit her when you were still young?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2701361 WN  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8660755\charrsid5717858 No, no, only neighbours. No, only - only just neighbours.
\par }}